{"title_page": "Leucania obsoleta", "text_new": "AwesomeAKO, editor\n\n1,483 records (1,483 in total) of being seen<ref>{{cite web |last1=O'Brien |first1=Avery |title=Leucania obsoleta |url=https://species.nbnatlas.org/species/NHMSYS0021144872 |website=NBN atlas |publisher=NBN atlas |accessdate=04/13/2020}}</ref>\n{{short description|Species of moth}}\n{{Taxobox\n| image = Leucania obsoleta FvL.jpg\n| image2 = Leucania_obsoleta.jpg\n| regnum = [[Animalia]]\n| phylum = [[Arthropoda]]\n| classis = [[Insecta]]\n| ordo = [[Lepidoptera]]\n| familia = [[Noctuidae]]\n| genus = ''[[Leucania]]''\n| species = '''''L. obsoleta'''''\n| binomial = ''Leucania obsoleta''\n| binomial_authority = ([[Jacob H\u00fcbner|H\u00fcbner]], 1803)\n}}\n'''''Leucania obsoleta''''', the '''obscure wainscot''', is a [[moth]] of the superfamily [[Noctuoidea]]. The species was [[Species description|first described]] by [[Jacob H\u00fcbner]] in 1803. It is found in Europe.\n\nThe length of the forewings is 15\u201318&nbsp;mm. The moth flies in one generation from early May to late July.{{ref|flight_season}}\n\nThe larvae feed on ''[[Phragmites]]'' species.\n\n==Notes==\n#{{Note|flight_season}}''The flight season refers to [[Belgium]] and the [[Netherlands]]. This may vary in other parts of the range.''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{cite web |last=Kimber |first=Ian |url=https://www.ukmoths.org.uk/species/leucania-obsoleta |title=73.302 BF2204 Obscure Wainscot ''Leucania obsoleta'' (H\u00fcbner, [1803]) |website=UKMoths |accessdate=1 July 2019}}\n*[http://www.lepiforum.de/lepiwiki.pl?Leucania_Obsoleta ''Lepiforum e.V.'']\n*[http://www.vlindernet.nl/vlindersoort.php?vlinderid=638&vq=Leucania ''De Vlinderstichting''] {{in lang|nl}}\nWritten and edited by Wikipedia family\n{{Taxonbar |from=Q2408899}}\n\n[[Category:Leucania]]\n[[Category:Moths of Europe]]\n[[Category:Moths of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Jacob H\u00fcbner]]\n\n\n{{Mythimnini-stub}}\n", "text_old": "AwesomeAKO, editor\n\n1,483 records (1,483 in total) of being seen<ref>{{cite web |last1=O'Brien |first1=Avery |title=Leucania obsoleta |url=https://species.nbnatlas.org/species/NHMSYS0021144872 |website=NBN atlas |publisher=NBN atlas |accessdate=04/13/2020}}</ref>\n{{short description|Species of moth}}\n{{Taxobox\n| image = Leucania obsoleta FvL.jpg\n| image2 = Leucania_obsoleta.jpg\n| regnum = [[Animalia]]\n| phylum = [[Arthropoda]]\n| classis = [[Insecta]]\n| ordo = [[Lepidoptera]]\n| familia = [[Noctuidae]]\n| genus = ''[[Leucania]]''\n| species = '''''L. obsoleta'''''\n| binomial = ''Leucania obsoleta''\n| binomial_authority = ([[Jacob H\u00fcbner|H\u00fcbner]], 1803)\n}}\n'''''Leucania obsoleta''''', the '''obscure wainscot''', is a [[moth]] of the superfamily [[Noctuoidea]]. The species was [[Species description|first described]] by [[Jacob H\u00fcbner]] in 1803. It is found in Europe.\n\nThe length of the forewings is 15\u201318&nbsp;mm. The moth flies in one generation from early May to late July.{{ref|flight_season}}\n\nThe larvae feed on ''[[Phragmites]]'' species.\n\n==Notes==\n#{{Note|flight_season}}''The flight season refers to [[Belgium]] and the [[Netherlands]]. This may vary in other parts of the range.''\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{cite web |last=Kimber |first=Ian |url=https://www.ukmoths.org.uk/species/leucania-obsoleta |title=73.302 BF2204 Obscure Wainscot ''Leucania obsoleta'' (H\u00fcbner, [1803]) |website=UKMoths |accessdate=1 July 2019}}\n*[http://www.lepiforum.de/lepiwiki.pl?Leucania_Obsoleta ''Lepiforum e.V.'']\n*[http://www.vlindernet.nl/vlindersoort.php?vlinderid=638&vq=Leucania ''De Vlinderstichting''] {{in lang|nl}}\nWritten and edited by Wikipedia family\n{{Taxonbar |from=Q2408899}}\n\n[[Category:Leucania]]\n[[Category:Moths of Europe]]\n[[Category:Moths of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Jacob H\u00fcbner]]\n\n\n{{Mythimnini-stub}}\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leucania_obsoleta"}
{"title_page": "Smash-Up, the Story of a Woman", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Smash-Up, the Story of a Woman\n| image          = Smash-Up, the Story of a Woman.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Stuart Heisler]]\n| producer       = [[Walter Wanger]]\n| writer         = Frank Cavett<br>[[John Howard Lawson]]<br>[[Dorothy Parker]]<br>Lionel Wiggam\n| starring       = [[Susan Hayward]]<br>[[Eddie Albert]]\n| music          = [[Frank Skinner (composer)|Frank Skinner]]\n| cinematography = [[Stanley Cortez]]\n| editing        = Milton Carruth\n| studio         = Walter Wanger Productions\n| distributor   = [[Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1947|03}}\n| runtime        = 103 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $1,360,286<ref name=\"wagner\">Matthew Bernstein, ''Walter Wagner: Hollywood Independent'', Minnesota Press, 2000 p443</ref>\n| gross          = $2,301,555<ref name=\"wagner\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Smash-Up, the Story of a Woman''''', also called '''''A Woman Destroyed''''',<ref>{{cite book | last=Higham | first=Charles | last2=Greenberg | first2=Joel | year = 1968 | title=Hollywood in the Forties | page=83 | publisher=A. Zwemmer Limited | location=London | isbn=<!--Not Given-->}}</ref> is a 1947 American [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] with elements of [[film noir]] which tells the story of a rising [[nightclub singer]] who marries another singer, whose career takes off, then falls into [[alcoholism]] after giving up her career for him. The film stars [[Susan Hayward]], [[Lee Bowman]], and [[Eddie Albert]], and was written by Frank Cavett, [[John Howard Lawson]], [[Dorothy Parker]], and Lionel Wiggam, and was directed by [[Stuart Heisler]]. [[Ethel Wales]] appears in an uncredited part.\n\nThe film was nominated for [[Academy Awards]] for [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress in a Leading Role]] ([[Susan Hayward]]) and [[Academy Award for Best Story|Best Writing, Original Story]].\n\n==Plot==\nIn a hospital, Angie Evans ([[Susan Hayward]]), her face bandaged, recounts the events that brought her here.\n\nA nightclub singer, Angie becomes involved with another singer, Ken Conway ([[Lee Bowman]]), whose career has yet to take off. Her agent Mike Dawson ([[Charles D. Brown]]) helps get Ken and piano accompanist Steve Anderson ([[Eddie Albert]]) a spot on a radio show singing cowboy songs. Ken sings a ballad on the day Angie, now his wife, gives birth to their daughter. The attention he gets leads to a new career opportunity.\n\nKen soon is a big success, gaining popularity and wealth, while Angie stays home, her career at a standstill. She begins to drink. Ken counts on her to present a sophisticated image for his new high-society friends and contacts, but her alcoholism worsens, so secretary Martha Gray ([[Marsha Hunt (actress, born 1917)|Marsha Hunt]]) comes to Ken's aid.\n\nIt isn't long before Angie is certain Martha and her husband are having an affair. Steve tries to intervene on Angie's behalf, but he can see Martha has fallen in love with Ken.\n\nAngie neglects the child, continues to drink, then creates a scene at a party. Ken asks for a divorce and custody. Mike helps Angie get work in a club. She is determined to stay sober so she can regain custody of her daughter. Instead, she ends up in a bar, and wakes the next morning in the apartment of strangers who found her passed out on their stairs.\n\nAngie kidnaps her daughter from the park while the nurse isn't watching. They go to a house in the country where Angie dutifully gives the child dinner and puts her to bed. After she sings her daughter to sleep, she forgets a lit cigarette in the room. Downstairs, she begins to drink and gets lost in memories. The child's shouts finally alert her and Angie rescues her from the flames, but herself suffers serious facial burns.\n\nRealizing that she has hit rock bottom, Angie is positive now she can move forward happily. Ken has talked things over with her doctor and feels that he would like to try to stand by her.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Susan Hayward]] as Angie Evans (singing dubbed by [[Peg LaCentra]]) \n* [[Lee Bowman]] as Ken Conway (singing dubbed by Hal Derwin) \n* [[Eddie Albert]] as Steve Anderson\n* [[Marsha Hunt (actress, born 1917)|Marsha Hunt]] as Martha Gray\n* [[Carl Esmond]] as Dr. Lorenz\n* [[Carleton Young]] as Fred Elliott\n* [[Charles D. Brown]] as Michael Dawson\n* Janet Murdoch as Miss Kirk, baby Angelica's nanny\n* Sharyn Payne as Angelica \"Angel\" Conway\n* [[Robert Shayne]] as Mr. Gordon\n* [[Erville Alderson]] as Farmer at Fire (uncredited)\n* [[Lee Shumway]] as Benson - Doorman (uncredited)\n\n==Reception==\nAccording to ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', the film earned $2&nbsp;million in US box office receipts in 1947.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/variety169-1948-01#page/n62/mode/1up \"Top Grossers of 1947\", ''Variety'', 7 January 1948 p 63]</ref>\n\nThe film lost $111,664 in its initial release.<ref name=\"wagner\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of American films of 1947]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb title|0039840}}\n* {{tcmdb title|id=90554}}\n* {{Internet Archive film|id=Smash-Up}}\n* {{AFI film|id=25355|title=Smash Up--The Story of a Woman}}\n\n{{Stuart Heisler}}\n{{Walter Wanger}}\n\n[[Category:1947 films]]\n[[Category:1940s drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films about alcoholism]]\n[[Category:Films about music and musicians]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Stuart Heisler]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Walter Wanger]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Dorothy Parker]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Frank Skinner]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Smash-Up, the Story of a Woman\n| image          = Smash-Up, the Story of a Woman.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Stuart Heisler]]\n| producer       = [[Walter Wanger]]\n| writer         = Frank Cavett<br>[[John Howard Lawson]]<br>[[Dorothy Parker]]<br>Lionel Wiggam\n| starring       = [[Susan Hayward]]<br>[[Eddie Albert]]\n| music          = [[Frank Skinner (composer)|Frank Skinner]]\n| cinematography = [[Stanley Cortez]]\n| editing        = Milton Carruth\n| studio         = Walter Wanger Productions\n| distributor   = [[Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1947|03}}\n| runtime        = 103 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $1,360,286<ref name=\"wagner\">Matthew Bernstein, ''Walter Wagner: Hollywood Independent'', Minnesota Press, 2000 p443</ref>\n| gross          = $2,301,555<ref name=\"wagner\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Smash-Up, the Story of a Woman''''', also called '''''A Woman Destroyed''''',<ref>{{cite book | last=Higham | first=Charles | last2=Greenberg | first2=Joel | year = 1968 | title=Hollywood in the Forties | page=83 | publisher=A. Zwemmer Limited | location=London | isbn=<!--Not Given-->}}</ref> is a 1947 American [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] with elements of [[film noir]] which tells the story of a rising [[nightclub singer]] who marries another singer, whose career takes off, then falls into [[alcoholism]] after giving up her career for him.  The film stars [[Susan Hayward]], [[Lee Bowman]], and [[Eddie Albert]], and was written by Frank Cavett, [[John Howard Lawson]], [[Dorothy Parker]], and Lionel Wiggam, and was directed by [[Stuart Heisler]]. [[Ethel Wales]] appears in an uncredited part.\n\nThe film was nominated for [[Academy Awards]] for [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress in a Leading Role]] ([[Susan Hayward]]) and [[Academy Award for Best Story|Best Writing, Original Story]].\n\n==Plot==\nIn a hospital, Angie Evans ([[Susan Hayward]]), her face bandaged, recounts the events that brought her here.\n\nA nightclub singer, Angie becomes involved with another singer, Ken Conway ([[Lee Bowman]]), whose career has yet to take off. Her agent Mike Dawson ([[Charles D. Brown]]) helps get Ken and piano accompanist Steve Anderson ([[Eddie Albert]]) a spot on a radio show singing cowboy songs. Ken sings a ballad on the day Angie, now his wife, gives birth to their daughter. The attention he gets leads to a new career opportunity.\n\nKen soon is a big success, gaining popularity and wealth, while Angie stays home, her career at a standstill. She begins to drink. Ken counts on her to present a sophisticated image for his new high-society friends and contacts, but her alcoholism worsens, so secretary Martha Gray ([[Marsha Hunt (actress, born 1917)|Marsha Hunt]]) comes to Ken's aid.\n\nIt isn't long before Angie is certain Martha and her husband are having an affair. Steve tries to intervene on Angie's behalf, but he can see Martha has fallen in love with Ken.\n\nAngie neglects the child, continues to drink, then creates a scene at a party. Ken asks for a divorce and custody. Mike helps Angie get work in a club. She is determined to stay sober so she can regain custody of her daughter. Instead, she ends up in a bar, and wakes the next morning in the apartment of strangers who found her passed out on their stairs.\n\nAngie kidnaps her daughter from the park while the nurse isn't watching. They go to a house in the country where Angie dutifully gives the child dinner and puts her to bed. After she sings her daughter to sleep, she forgets a lit cigarette in the room. Downstairs, she begins to drink and gets lost in memories. The child's shouts finally alert her and Angie rescues her from the flames, but herself suffers serious facial burns.\n\nRealizing that she has hit rock bottom, Angie is positive now she can move forward happily. Ken has talked things over with her doctor and feels that he would like to try to stand by her.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Susan Hayward]] as Angie Evans (singing dubbed by [[Peg LaCentra]]) \n* [[Lee Bowman]] as Ken Conway (singing dubbed by Hal Derwin) \n* [[Eddie Albert]] as Steve Anderson\n* [[Marsha Hunt (actress, born 1917)|Marsha Hunt]] as Martha Gray\n* [[Carl Esmond]] as Dr. Lorenz\n* [[Carleton Young]] as Fred Elliott\n* [[Charles D. Brown]] as Michael Dawson\n* Janet Murdoch as Miss Kirk, baby Angelica's nanny\n* Sharyn Payne as Angelica \"Angel\" Conway\n* [[Robert Shayne]] as Mr. Gordon\n* [[Erville Alderson]] as Farmer at Fire (uncredited)\n* [[Lee Shumway]] as Benson - Doorman (uncredited)\n\n==Reception==\nAccording to ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', the film earned $2 million in US box office receipts in 1947.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/variety169-1948-01#page/n62/mode/1up \"Top Grossers of 1947\", ''Variety'', 7 January 1948 p 63]</ref>\n\nThe film lost $111,664 in its initial release.<ref name=\"wagner\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of American films of 1947]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb title|0039840}}\n* {{tcmdb title|id=90554}}\n* {{Internet Archive film|id=Smash-Up}}\n* {{AFI film|id=25355|title=Smash Up--The Story of a Woman}}\n\n{{Stuart Heisler}}\n{{Walter Wanger}}\n\n[[Category:1947 films]]\n[[Category:1940s drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films about alcoholism]]\n[[Category:Films about music and musicians]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Stuart Heisler]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Walter Wanger]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Dorothy Parker]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Frank Skinner]]\n", "name_user": "JHunterJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, replaced: 2 million \u2192 2\u00a0million", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smash-Up,_the_Story_of_a_Woman"}
{"title_page": "Mass shootings in the United States", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Incidents involving multiple victims of firearm-related violence}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n[[File:Total deaths in US mass shootings.png|thumb|Total deaths in U.S. mass shootings from 1982\u20132012, shaded to indicate the beginning and end of the [[Federal Assault Weapons Ban]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2012/12/mass-shootings-mother-jones-full-data|title=US Mass Shootings, 1982\u20132019: Data from Mother Jones' investigation|last1=Follman|first1=Mark|last2=Aronsen|first2=Gavin|last3=Pan|first3=Deanna|date=4 August 2019|website=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]|accessdate=10 August 2019}}</ref>]]\n[[File:2015 Mass Shootings (cropped).jpg|thumb|Locations of US mass shootings in 2015, according to ''Shooting Tracker''.]]\n\n[[Mass shooting]]s are incidents involving multiple victims of all the other kids with the pumped up kicks [[Gun violence in the United States|firearm-related violence]]. The precise inclusion criteria are disputed, and there is no broadly accepted definition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/10/04/the-squishy-definition-of-mass-shooting-complicates-media-coverage/|title=The squishy definition of 'mass shooting' complicates media coverage|last=Borchers|first=Callum|date=October 4, 2017|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=August 26, 2018|quote=...'mass shooting' is a term without a universally-accepted definition.}}</ref><ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://fas.org/sgp/crs/misc/R43004.pdf|title=Public Mass Shootings in the United States|last=Bjelopera|first=Jerome|date=March 18, 2013|website=Congressional Research Service|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130909213006/http://www.fas.org/sgp/crs/misc/R43004.pdf|archive-date=2013-09-09|url-status=dead|access-date=2018-08-26|quote=There is no broadly agreed-to, specific conceptualization of this issue, so this report uses its own definition for public mass shootings.}}</ref><ref name=\"politifact2018\">{{cite web|last1=Greenberg|last2=Jacobson| last3=Valverde|first1=Jon|first2=Louis|first3=Miriam|title=What we know about mass shootings |url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/article/2018/feb/14/what-we-know-about-mass-shootings/|website=[[PolitiFact]]|publisher=[[Tampa Bay Times]]|accessdate=February 20, 2018|date=February 14, 2018|quote=As noted above, there is no widely accepted definition of mass shootings. People use either broad or restrictive definitions of mass shootings to reinforce their stance on gun control. After the 2012 Sandy Hook school shooting, Congress defined \"mass killings\" as three or more homicides in a single incident. The definition was intended to clarify when the U.S. Attorney General could assist state and local authorities in investigations of violent acts and shootings in places of public use.}}</ref> One definition is an act of public firearm violence\u2014excluding gang killings, [[domestic violence]], or terrorist acts sponsored by an organization\u2014in which a shooter kills at least four victims. Using this definition, one study found that nearly one-third of the world's public mass shootings between 1966 and 2012 (90 of 292 incidents) occurred in the United States.<ref name=\"CNN why\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last=Lankford|first=Adam|authorlink=Adam Lankford|date=2016|title=Public Mass Shooters and Firearms: A Cross-National Study of 171 Countries |url=http://www.ingentaconnect.com/contentone/springer/vav/2016/00000031/00000002/art00001?crawler=true |journal=Violence and Victims|volume=31|issue=2|access-date=May 3, 2018}}</ref> Using a similar definition, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' records 163 mass shootings in the United States between 1967 and June 2019.<ref name=\"50years\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2018/national/mass-shootings-in-america/|title=The terrible numbers that grow with each mass shooting|last1=Berkowitz|first1=Bonnie|date=|work=[[Washington Post]]|accessdate=November 5, 2017|last2=Gamio|first2=Lazaro|last3=Lu|first3=Denise|last4=Uhrmacher|first4=Kevin|last5=Lindeman|first5=Todd}}</ref> \n\n[[Gun Violence Archive]], frequently cited by the press, defines a mass shooting as firearm violence resulting in at least four people being shot at roughly the same time and location, excluding the perpetrator.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/report-u-s-averages-nearly-one-mass-shooting-per-day-so-far-in-2017/|title=Report: U.S. averages nearly one mass shooting per day so far in 2017|last=|first=|date=|website=CBS News|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gunviolencearchive.org/methodology|title=General Methodology|last=|first=|date=|website=Gun Violence Archive|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=}}</ref> Using this definition, there have been 2,128 mass shootings since 2013, roughly one per day.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/ng-interactive/2017/oct/02/america-mass-shootings-gun-violence|title=Mass shootings in the US: there have been 1,624 in 1,870 days|date=|newspaper=The Guardian|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=|last1=Morris|first1=Sam|last2=Team|first2=Guardian US Interactive|last3=Morris|first3=Sam|last4=Team|first4=Guardian US Interactive}}</ref>\n\nAccording to some studies, the United States has had more mass shootings than any other country.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-leads-world-in-mass-shootings-1443905359 |title=U.S. Leads World in Mass Shootings|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate= October 2, 2017|first1=Joe|last1=Palazzolo|first2=Alexis|last2=Flynn|date=October 3, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN why\"  /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/science/sciencenow/la-sci-sn-united-states-mass-shooting-20150824-story.html|first=Melissa|last=Healy|title=Why the U.S. is No. 1 \u2013 in mass shootings|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=August 24, 2015|accessdate= October 2, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news| url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2015/08/united-states-world-mass-shooters/|first=Samantha|last=Michaels |title=The United States Has Had More Mass Shootings Than Any Other Country|work=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]|date=August 23, 2015|accessdate=October 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2017/10/03/americas/us-gun-statistics/index.html|title=How US gun culture compares with the world in five charts|first=Kara|last=Fox|date=March 9, 2018|work=[[CNN]]}}</ref> Shooters generally either die by suicide afterwards or are restrained or killed by [[law enforcement officer]]s or [[civilian]]s.<ref>{{Citation|last1=Blair|first1=John Pete|last2=Schweit|first2=Katherine W.|title=A Study of Active Shooter Incidents, 2000\u20132013|place=Washington, DC|publisher=[[Texas State University]] and [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]]|date=2014|url=https://www.fbi.gov/file-repository/active-shooter-study-2000-2013-1.pdf}}</ref> However, mass shootings accounted for less than two-tenths of 1% (0.2%) of all homicides in the United States between 2000 and 2016.<ref name=\"pewtrusts.org\">https://www.pewtrusts.org/en/research-and-analysis/blogs/stateline/2019/08/08/one-third-of-mass-shootings-committed-by-people-with-mental-illness-study-says</ref>\n\n==Definitions==\nThere is no fixed definition of a mass shooting in the United States.<ref name=\"politifact2018\" /><ref>{{cite news |first=Elyssa |last=Cherney |date=August 5, 2019 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-cb-mass-shootings-language-definition-gun-violence-20190805-dv2g5lcumbeq3gji4dnycx7j74-story.html |title=The Same Weekend as Massacres in El Paso and Dayton, 15 People Were Shot in 2 Chicago Incidents. Why Aren't Those Called Mass Shootings Too? |work=Chicago Tribune |access-date=August 7, 2019 |quote=Different organizations use a variety of measures to determine whether an act of gun violence meets the criteria of a mass shooting.... How you define the term results in vastly different counts: The Gun Violence Archive has tallied 255 mass shootings in 2019 so far, while Mother Jones lists the number at seven. Some databases also exclude gang-related or domestic shootings.... Researchers on both sides of the spectrum say that data about mass shootings can be misleading if not presented with a clear methodology.}}</ref> The Investigative Assistance for Violent Crimes Act of 2012, signed into law in January 2013, defines a \"mass killing\" as one resulting in at least 3 victims, excluding the perpetrator.<ref>{{cite web|title=H.R. 2076 (112th): Investigative Assistance for Violent Crimes Act of 2012|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/112/hr2076/text|website=govtrack.us|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=February 20, 2018|quote=(I)the term mass killings means 3 or more killings in a single incident;}}</ref><ref name=\"politifact2018\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Ingraham|first=Christopher|title=What makes a 'mass shooting' in America|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2015/12/03/what-makes-a-mass-shooting-in-america/|accessdate=November 5, 2017|work=[[Washington Post]]|date=December 3, 2015|quote=\"''But starting in 2013, federal statutes defined \"mass killing\" as three or more people killed, regardless of weapons.''\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Follman|first=Mark|title=What Exactly Is A Mass Shooting|url=https://www.motherjones.com/mojo/2012/08/what-is-a-mass-shooting|publisher=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]|accessdate=August 9, 2015|quote=In January 2013, a mandate for federal investigation of mass shootings authorized by President Barack Obama lowered that baseline to three or more victims killed.}}</ref> In 2015, the [[Congressional Research Service]] does not define a mass shooting but does define a public mass shooting \u2014 for the purposes of its report entitled \u201cMass Murder with Firearms\u201d \u2014 as \"a multiple homicide incident in which four or more victims are murdered with firearms, within one event, and in one or more locations in close proximity\". The CRS further states that its report \"attempts to refine the relatively broad concept of mass shooting [...] into a narrower formulation: public mass shootings.\" <ref name=\"fas\">{{cite web|last1=Krouse|first1=William J.|last2=Richardson|first2=Daniel J.|title=Mass Murder with Firearms: Incidents and Victims, 1999\u20132013| url=https://fas.org/sgp/crs/misc/R44126.pdf| website=FAS.org|publisher=Congressional Research Service|accessdate=October 28, 2019|date=July 30, 2015}}</ref> A broader definition, as used by the Gun Violence Archive, is that of \"4 or more shot or killed, not including the shooter\".<ref name=\"GVA Methodology\">{{cite web|title=General Methodology|url=http://www.gunviolencearchive.org/methodology|website=[[Gun Violence Archive]]|accessdate=February 21, 2018}}</ref> This definition, of four people shot regardless of whether or not that results in injury or death, is often used by the media, press, and non-profit organizations.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nichols|first=Chris|title=How is a 'mass shooting' defined?|url=http://www.politifact.com/california/article/2017/oct/04/mass-shooting-what-does-it-mean/|website=[[PolitiFact]] California|accessdate=February 21, 2018|date=October 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN2\">{{cite news|last=Christensen|first=Jen|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/08/27/health/u-s-most-mass-shootings/|title=Why the U.S. has the most mass shootings|date=August 28, 2015|work=[[CNN]]}}</ref><ref name=\"shooting tracker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.massshootingtracker.org/about|title=About the Mass Shooting Tracker|website=Mass Shooting Tracker|accessdate=June 13, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180104222719/https://www.massshootingtracker.org/about|archive-date=January 4, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"MyUser_BBC_13_June_2016c\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-36519450|title=Orlando club shootings: Full fury of gun battle emerges|work=[[BBC News]]|date=June 13, 2016|accessdate= June 13, 2016}} Cites Mass Shooting Tracker</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Axelrod|first=Jim|title=Are Americans becoming \"numb\" to mass shootings?|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/are-americans-becoming-numb-to-mass-shootings/|work=[[CBS News]]|accessdate=February 21, 2018|date=November 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Frequency==\n[[File:Lasvegassignflowers.jpg|thumb|Memorial at the [[Welcome to Fabulous Las Vegas sign]] following the [[2017 Las Vegas shooting]], which resulted in 58 people being killed and 422 non-fatal injuries.]]\nSome studies indicate that the rate at which public mass shootings occur has tripled since 2011. Between 1982 and 2011, a mass shooting occurred roughly once every 200 days. However, between 2011 and 2014, that rate has accelerated greatly with at least one mass shooting occurring every 64 days in the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|first1=Amy P. |last1=Cohen|first2=Deborah|last2=Azrael|first3=Matthew|last3=Miller |url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2014/10/mass-shootings-increasing-harvard-research/#|title=Rate of mass shootings has tripled since 2011, new research from Harvard shows|work=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]|date=October 15, 2014|access-date=December 13, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn recent years, the number of public mass shootings has increased substantially, although there has been an approximately 50% decrease in firearm homicides in the nation overall since 1993. The decrease in firearm homicides has been attributed to better policing, a better economy and environmental factors such as the removal of lead from gasoline.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2015/12/03/weve-had-a-massive-decline-in-gun-violence-in-the-united-states-heres-why/|title=We've had a massive decline in gun violence in the United States. Here's why.|last=Ehrenfreund|first=Max|date=December 3, 2015|work=[[Washington Post]]|access-date=December 13, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\n===Differing sources===\nA comprehensive report by ''[[USA Today]]'' tracked all mass killings from 2006 through 2017 in which the perpetrator willfully killed 4 or more people. For mass killings by firearm for instance, it found 271 incidents with a total of 1,358 victims.<ref name=\"usatoday\">{{cite news|title=Behind the Bloodshed|url=http://www.gannett-cdn.com/GDContent/mass-killings/index.html|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=December 3, 2015}}</ref> ''[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]'' listed seven mass shootings, defined as indiscriminate rampages in public places resulting in four or more victims killed,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2012/07/mass-shootings-map |title=A Guide to Mass Shootings in America |publisher=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]] |date=June 12, 2016 |first1=Mark|last1=Follman|first2=Gavin |last2=Aronsen |first3=Deanna |last3=Pan |accessdate= June 13, 2016}}</ref> in the U.S. for 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2012/12/mass-shootings-mother-jones-full-data |title=US Mass Shootings, 1982\u20132016: Data From Mother Jones' Investigation |work=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]|date= |first1=Mark |last1=Follman|first2=Gavin |last2=Aronsen|first3=Deanna|last3=Pan|accessdate=June 13, 2016}} Original date December 28, 2012; list updated every 5 minutes. Figures for years 2011\u20132015: 3, 7, 5, 4, 7.</ref> An analysis by [[Michael Bloomberg|Michael Bloomberg's]] gun violence prevention group, ''[[Everytown for Gun Safety]]'', identified 110 mass shootings, defined as shootings in which at least four people were murdered with a firearm, between January 2009 and July 2014; at least 57% were related to domestic or family violence.<ref name=\"alter2\">{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/07/17/domestic-violence-gun_n_5595898.html|title=Mass Shooting Analysis Finds Strong Domestic Violence Connection|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date= July 18, 2014| first=Melissa| last=Jeltsen|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"bloombergstudy\">{{cite web|url=http://everytownresearch.org/reports/mass-shootings-analysis/|title=Analysis of Mass Shootings |publisher=[[Everytown for Gun Safety]]|date=August 20, 2015|accessdate=June 13, 2016}} This analysis has later figures than reported in the article</ref>\n\nOther media outlets have reported that hundreds of mass shootings take place in the United States in a single calendar year, citing a crowd-funded website known as ''Shooting Tracker'' which defines a mass shooting as having four or more people injured or killed.<ref name=\"shooting tracker\"/> In December 2015, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' reported that there had been 355 mass shootings in the United States so far that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2015/12/02/the-san-bernardino-mass-shooting-is-the-second-today-and-the-355th-this-year/|title=The San Bernardino shooting is the second mass shooting today and the 355th this year|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=December 2, 2015|accessdate=December 16, 2015}}</ref> In August 2015, ''The Washington Post'' reported that the United States was averaging one mass shooting per day.<ref name=one>{{cite news|last=Ingraham|first=Christopher|title=We're now averaging more than one mass shooting per day in 2015|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonkblog/wp/2015/08/26/were-now-averaging-more-than-one-mass-shooting-per-day-in-2015/|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=September 6, 2015}}</ref> An earlier report had indicated that in 2015 alone, there had been 294 mass shootings that killed or injured 1,464 people.<ref>{{cite web|title=More than one mass shooting happens per day in the U.S., data shows|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/one-mass-shooting-happens-per-day-u-s-data-shows/|website=PBS NewsHour|date=October 2, 2015}}</ref> ''Shooting Tracker'' and ''Mass Shooting Tracker'', the two sites that the media have been citing, have been criticized for using a broader criteria \u2013 counting four victims injured as a mass shooting \u2013 thus producing much higher figures.<ref name=\"NYTDec_2015\">{{cite news|first=Mark|last=Follman| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/04/opinion/how-many-mass-shootings-are-there-really.html?_r=1|title=How Many Mass Shootings Are There, Really?|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 3, 2015|accessdate=December 6, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Elizabeth|last=Stuart|url=http://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/news/number-of-us-mass-shootings-greatly-exaggerated-in-media-acclaimed-researcher-states-7872731|title=Number of U.S. Mass Shootings Greatly Exaggerated in Media, Acclaimed Researcher States|work=[[Phoenix New Times]]|date=December 7, 2015|accessdate=December 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to ''The New York Times'', the majority of perpetrators they have published stories about are white males who act alone.<ref name=msa>{{cite news|last=Victor|first=Daniel| date=February 17, 2018|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/17/us/mass-murderers.html|title=Mass Shooters Are All Different. Except for One Thing: Most Are Men|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=April 10, 2018 |quote=About the only thing almost all of them have in common is that they are men. [...] Examining past New York Times coverage of mass shootings reveals some shared tendencies of the gunmen, including the fact that they are most commonly white}}</ref> According to most analyses and studies, the proportion of mass shooters in the United States who are white is slightly less than the proportion of white people in the [[Demography of the United States|general population of the US]], however the proportion of male mass shooters is considerably greater than the proportion of males.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2017/10/what-the-white-mass-shooter-myth-gets-right-and-wrong-about-killers-demographics.html|title=What the White Mass-Shooter Myth Gets Right and Wrong About Killers' Demographics|last=Engber|first=Daniel|date=2017-10-06|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-08-04|quote=\"roughly 70 percent of the shooters in mass killings were white\u2014certainly a majority. But according to Census Bureau estimates for 2012, whites accounted for 73.9 percent of all Americans\" \"men are even more overrepresented among mass shooters and mass killers than they are among \u201cnormal\u201d killers\"}}</ref>\n\n==Contributing factors==\nSeveral possible factors may work together to create a fertile environment for [[mass murder]] in the United States.<ref name=\"No. 1\">{{cite news|last=Healy|first=Melissa|title=Why the U.S. is No. 1 \u2013 in mass shootings|url=http://beta.latimes.com/science/sciencenow/la-sci-sn-united-states-mass-shooting-20150824-story.html|accessdate=November 6, 2017|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=August 24, 2015}}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Most commonly suggested include:\n\n# Higher accessibility and ownership of guns.<ref name=\"No. 1\" /><ref name=\"CNN why\">{{cite news|last=Christensen|first=Jen|title=Why the US has the most mass shootings|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/08/27/health/u-s-most-mass-shootings/index.html|work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=November 6, 2017|date=October 5, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/> The US has the highest [[Estimated number of guns per capita by country|per-capita gun ownership in the world]] with 120.5 firearms per 100 people; the second highest is Yemen with 52.8 firearms per 100 people.<ref name=\"No. 1\" />\n# [[mental disorder|Mental illness]]<ref>{{cite news|title=The real mental health issue behind gun violence|work=[[CNN]]|date=January 25, 2016|accessdate=November 7, 2017|first=Emanuella|last=Grinberg|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/01/25/health/gun-violence-mental-health-issue/index.html}}</ref> and its treatment (or the lack thereof) with psychiatric drugs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/blog/mad-in-america/201101/psychiatric-drugs-and-violence-review-fda-data-finds-link|first=Robert|last=Whitaker|title=Psychiatric Drugs and Violence: A Review of FDA Data Finds A Link|website=[[Psychology Today]]|date=January 5, 2011|accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref> This is controversial.<ref>{{cite web|last=Campbell|first=Holly|title=Inside the mind of a mass murderer|url=http://wane.com/2015/12/02/inside-the-mind-of-a-mass-murderer/|publisher=[[WANE-TV]]|date=December 2, 2015|accessdate=November 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=James Alan|last=Fox|date=January 16, 2011|url=http://www.boston.com/community/blogs/crime_punishment/2011/01/the_real_causes_of_mass_murder.html|title=The real causes of mass murder| work=[[Boston.com]]|accessdate=November 9, 2017}}</ref> Many of the mass shooters in the U.S. suffered from mental illness, but the estimated number of mental illness cases has not increased as significantly as the number of mass shootings.<ref name=\"CNN why\" /> \n# The desire to seek revenge for a long history of being [[bullied]] at school and/or at the workplace. In recent years, citizens calling themselves \"targeted individual\" have cited adult bullying campaigns as a reason for their deadly violence.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Burgess| first1=Ann Wolbert|first2=Christina|last2=Garbarino|first3=Mary I. |last3=Carlson| title=Pathological teasing and bullying turned deadly: Shooters and suicide|journal=Victims and Offenders|volume=1|issue=1|date=2006|pages= 1\u201314| doi=10.1080/15564880500498705}}</ref>\n# The widespread chronic gap between people's expectations for themselves and their actual achievement,<ref name=\"No. 1\" /> and [[individualistic culture]].<ref name=europe>{{cite news|last=Dorell|first=Oren|title=In Europe, fewer mass killings due to culture not guns|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2012/12/17/guns-mass-killings-worldwide/1776191/|work=[[USA Today]]|date=December 18, 2012|accessdate=August 11, 2015}}</ref> Some analysts and commentators place the blame on contemporary [[capitalism]] and [[neoliberalism]].<ref>{{cite news |last= McIntyre|first=Niamh|date=April 16, 2015 |title=This Theorist Believes That Capitalism Creates Mass Murderers by Causing People to 'Malfunction'|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/wd7eyw/berardi-interview|work=Vice |location= |access-date=August 5, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1= Wolff|first1=Richard D.|last2= Fraad|first2=Harriet|date=November 8, 2017 |title=American hyper-capitalism breeds the lonely, alienated men who become mass killers|url=https://www.salon.com/2017/11/08/american-hyper-capitalism-breeds-the-lonely-alienated-men-who-become-mass-killers_partner/|work=Salon |location= |access-date=August 5, 2019|authorlink1=Richard D. Wolff|authorlink2=Harriet Fraad}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Norton |first=Ben |date=August 4, 2019|title=It's not just Trump who unleashed the fascist massacre in El Paso \u2013 It's capitalism and imperialism as a system |url=https://bennorton.com/trump-fascist-massacre-el-paso-capitalism-imperialism-system/|work=Bennorton.com |location= |access-date=August 5, 2019|authorlink=Ben Norton}}</ref>\n# Desire for fame and notoriety.<ref name=\"No. 1\" /><ref name=\"CNN why\" /> Also, mass shooters learn from one another through \"media contagion,\" that is, \"the mass media coverage of them and the proliferation of social media sites that tend to glorify the shooters and downplay the victims.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Mills|first=Kim|date=August 4, 2016| title=\"Media Contagion\" Is Factor in Mass Shootings, Study Says|url=https://www.apa.org/news/press/releases/2016/08/media-contagion.aspx|publisher=APA}}</ref><ref>{{cite conference|last1=Johnston|first1=J.B.|last2=Joy|first2=A.|title=Mass Shootings and the Media Contagion Effect|book-title=124th Annual Convention of the American Psychological Association| publisher=APA|date=August 4, 2016|url=https://www.apa.org/news/press/releases/2016/08/media-contagion-effect.pdf}}</ref>\n# The [[copycat crime|copycat phenomenon]].<ref name=\"CNN why\" />\n# Failure of government background checks due to incomplete databases and/or staff shortages.<ref>{{cite news|last=Johnson| first=Kevin|title=Texas Church Shooting Background Check Failure|work=[[USA Today]]|date=November 9, 2017|accessdate=November 17, 2017|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2017/11/09/texas-church-shooting-background-check-breakdown-highlights-federal-gun-record-problems/847947001/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Barrett |first=Devlin|title=FBI's Gun Background Check Database Missing Records|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=November 10, 2017| accessdate=November 17, 2017|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-fbi-gun-background-check-system-missing-records-20171110-story.html}}</ref>\n\nA panel of mental health and law enforcement experts has estimated that roughly one-third of acts of mass violence \u2014 defined as crimes in which four or more people were killed \u2014 since the 1990s were committed by people with a serious mental illness. However, the study emphasized that people with serious mental illness are responsible for less than 4% of all the violent acts committed in the United States.<ref name=\"pewtrusts.org\"/>\n\n==Weapons used==\nSeveral types of guns have been used in mass shootings in the United States. A 2014 study conducted by [[James Alan Fox|Dr. James Fox]] of 142 shootings found that 88 (62%) were committed with handguns of all types; 68 (48%) with semi-automatic handguns, 20 (14%) with revolvers, 35 (25%) with semi-automatic rifles, and 19 (13%) with shotguns.<ref name=help>{{cite news |url=https://psmag.com/news/simple-facts-mass-shootings-arent-simple-72055/|last=Todd|first=Michael|title=The Simple Facts About Mass Shootings Aren't Simple at All|work=Pacific Standard|accessdate=August 21, 2018|date=December 23, 2013}}</ref><ref name=numbers>{{cite book|last1=Schildkraut|first1=Jaclyn|last2=Elsass|first2=H. Jaymi|title=Mass Shootings: Media, Myths, and Realities: Media, Myths, and Realities|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JxJ1CwAAQBAJ|year=2016|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-4408-3653-4}}</ref><ref name=cnn>{{cite web|url=https://www.mrc.org/biasalerts/criminology-professor-cnns-tapper-mass-shootings-arent-epidemic/|title=Criminology Professor to CNN's Tapper: Mass Shootings Aren't an 'Epidemic'|publisher=Media Research Center|accessdate=August 20, 2018|date=June 16, 2014}}</ref> The study was conducted using the [[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]] database of mass shootings from 1982 to 2018.<ref name=mother>{{cite news|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2012/12/mass-shootings-mother-jones-full-data/3//|title=US Mass Shootings, 1982\u20132018: Data From Mother Jones' Investigation| work=Mother Jones |accessdate=August 20, 2018|date=June 28, 2018}}</ref> [[High capacity magazine]]s were used in approximately half of mass shootings.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fisher|first=Marc|title=The AR-15: 'America's rifle' or illegitimate killing machine?|url=http://wapo.st/2BZXJAh?tid=ss_mail|accessdate=May 11, 2018|work=The Washington Post|date=February 15, 2018|quote=...high-capacity magazines have been used in more than half of mass shootings over four decades, according to several studies.}}</ref> Semi-automatic rifles have been used in six of the ten deadliest mass shooting events.<ref>{{cite news|title=The facts on mass shootings, guns in the United States|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/article/2018/may/18/facts-mass-shootings-guns-united-states/|accessdate=June 11, 2018| work=PolitiFact|date=May 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Pearce |first=Matt| title=Mass shootings are getting deadlier. And the latest ones all have something new in common: The AR-15| url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-ar-15-story.html|accessdate=May 11, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|date=February 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Deadliest mass shootings since 1949==\n<!-- This table is only a summary. Full coverage of each attack is given in their respective articles. -->{{Main|List of mass shootings in the United States}}\n\nThe following mass shootings are the deadliest to have occurred in modern U.S. history (1949 to present). Only incidents with ten or more victim fatalities are included.<ref name=\"CNN April\">{{cite news|title=Deadliest Mass Shootings in Modern US History Fast Facts|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2013/09/16/us/20-deadliest-mass-shootings-in-u-s-history-fast-facts/index.html|work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=April 6, 2018|date=April 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n:{{dagger}} Was previously the deadliest mass shooting\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! !! Incident !! data-sort-type=number| Year !! Location !! data-sort-type=number| Deaths !! data-sort-type=number| Injuries !! Type of firearm(s) used !! Ref(s)\n|-\n! 1\n| [[2017 Las Vegas shooting|Las Vegas shooting]] || 2017 || [[Paradise, Nevada]] || 58 <small>(plus 1 [[Perpetrator|perp.]])</small> || 851 (422 from gunfire) ||Automatic and semi-automatic rifles and revolver || <ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news|title=Deadliest Mass Shootings in Modern US History Fast Facts|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/09/16/us/20-deadliest-mass-shootings-in-u-s-history-fast-facts/index.html|work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=November 5, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"same\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/texas-gunman-rifle-las-vegas-newtown-mass-shooters-article-1.3614966|first=Reuven|last=Blau|title=Texas gunman used same rifle as Las Vegas, Newtown mass shooters|work=[[New York Daily News]]|date=November 6, 2017|access-date=November 7, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n! 2\n| [[Orlando nightclub shooting]] {{dagger}} || 2016 || [[Orlando, Florida]] || 49 <small>(plus 1 perp.)</small> || 53 || Semi-automatic rifle and pistol  || <ref name=\"CNN\" /><ref name=\"same\" />\n|-\n! 3\n| [[Virginia Tech shooting]] {{dagger}} || 2007 || [[Blacksburg, Virginia]] || 32 <small>(plus 1 perp.)</small> || 23 (17 from gunfire) || Semi-automatic pistols || <ref name=\"CNN\" />\n|-\n! 4\n| [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting]] || 2012 || [[Newtown, Connecticut]] || 27 <small>(plus 1 perp.)</small> || 2 || Semi-automatic rifle and pistol || <ref name=\"CNN\" />\n|-\n! 5\n| [[Sutherland Springs church shooting]] || 2017 || [[Sutherland Springs, Texas]] || 26 <small>(plus 1 perp.)</small><ref group=\"fn\" name=\"fetus\">The fatality total includes an unborn child.</ref> || 20 || Semi-automatic rifle || <ref>{{cite web|last=Carissimo|first=Justin|title=26 dead in shooting at church in Sutherland Springs, Texas| url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/texas-church-shooting-devin-patrick-kelley-first-baptist-church-sutherland-springs-live-updates/|website=[[CBS News]]|accessdate=November 6, 2017|date=November 6, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"same\" />\n|-\n! 6\n| [[Luby's shooting]] {{dagger}} || 1991 || [[Killeen, Texas]] || 23 <small>(plus 1 perp.)</small> || 27 || Semi-automatic pistols || <ref name=\"CNN\" />\n|-\n! 7\n| [[2019 El Paso shooting|El Paso Walmart shooting]] || 2019 || [[El Paso, Texas]] || 22 || 24 || Semi-automatic rifle ||<ref>{{cite news|first1=Andrew|last1=Blankstein|first2=Minyvonne|last2=Burke|title=El Paso shooting: 20 people dead, at least 26 injured, suspect in custody, police say|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/active-shooter-near-el-paso-mall-police-responding-n1039001|publisher=[[NBC News]]|date=August 3, 2019|accessdate=August 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Maxouris |first1=Christina |last2=Andone |first2=Dakin |last3=Chavez |first3=Nicole |last4=Levenson |first4=Eric |title=El Paso shooting death toll rises to 22 in anti-immigrant massacre |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/08/05/us/el-paso-shooting-monday/index.html |website=CNN |accessdate=5 August 2019 |date=5 August 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! 8\n| [[San Ysidro McDonald's massacre]] {{dagger}} || 1984 || [[San Diego, California]] || 21 <small>(plus 1 perp.)</small> || 19 || Semi-automatic carbine, pistols, and shotgun || <ref name=\"CNN\" />\n|-\n! 9\n| [[Stoneman Douglas High School shooting]] || 2018 || [[Parkland, Florida]] || 17 || 17 || Semi-automatic rifle || <ref>{{cite news|first1= Emanuella |last1=Grinberg|first2=Eric|last2=Levensen|title=At least 17 dead in Florida school shooting, law enforcement says|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/02/14/us/florida-high-school-shooting/index.html|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=February 14, 2018|accessdate=February 14, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! 10\n| [[University of Texas tower shooting]] {{dagger}} || 1966 || [[Austin, Texas]] || 16 <small>(plus 1 perp.)</small><ref group=\"fn\" name=\"victim\">plus 1 victim who died due to complications in 2001)</ref><ref group=\"fn\" name=\"fetus\"/> || 31 || [[Bolt-action]] rifle, [[Semi-automatic firearm|semi-automatic]] carbine, revolver, [[Semi-automatic firearm|semi-automatic]] pistols, and [[pump-action]] shotgun || <ref name=\"CNN\" />\n|-\n! rowspan=\"3\"| 11\n| [[Edmond post office shooting]] || 1986 || [[Edmond, Oklahoma]] || 14 <small>(plus 1 perp.)</small> || 6 || Semi-automatic pistols || <ref name=\"CNN\" />\n|-\n| [[2015 San Bernardino attack|San Bernardino attack]] || 2015 || [[San Bernardino, California]] || 14 <small>(plus 2 perps.)</small> || 24 || Semi-automatic rifles || <ref name=\"CNN\" /><ref name=\"same\" />\n|-\n| [[2009 Fort Hood shooting|Fort Hood shooting]] || 2009 || [[Killeen, Texas]] || 14<ref group=\"fn\" name=\"fetus\"/> || 32 <small>(plus 1 perp.)</small> || Semi-automatic pistol and revolver || <ref>{{cite web|last1=Cole|first1=Matthew |last2=Thomas|first2=Pierre|last3=Ryan|first3=Jason|last4=Esposito|first4=Richard|title='Cop Killer' Gun Used In Ft. Hood Shooting, Officials Said|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Blotter/cop-killer-gun-thought-ft-hood-shooting/story?id=9019521 |website=[[ABC News]]|accessdate=October 30, 2018 |language=en |date=November 19, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Carter|first=Chelsea J.|title=Nidal Hasan convicted in Fort Hood shootings|url=https://www.cnn.com/2013/08/23/justice/nidal-hasan-court-martial-friday/index.html |website=[[CNN]] |accessdate=October 30, 2018 |language=en |date=August 23, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"5\"| 14\n| [[Howard Unruh|Camden shootings]] {{dagger}} || 1949 || [[Camden, New Jersey]] || 13 || 3 || Semi-automatic pistol || <ref>{{cite news |date=September 7, 1949|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|title=Veteran Kills 12 in Mad Rampage on Camden Street |first=Meyer|last=Berger|authorlink=Meyer Berger |accessdate=July 6, 2018|url=http://www.pulitzer.org/article/mass-shooting-tight-deadline|quote=Howard B. Unruh, 28 years old, a mild, soft-spoken veteran of many armored artillery battles in Italy, France, Austria, Belgium and Germany, killed twelve persons with a war souvenir Luger pistol in his home block in East Camden this morning. He wounded four others.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Story of the First Mass Murder in U.S. History |url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/story-first-mass-murder-us-history-180956927/ |magazine=[[Smithsonian Magazine]] |publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution]] |first=Patrick |last=Sauer |date=October 14, 2015 |quote=He went into his apartment, uncased his German Luger P08, a 9mm pistol he\u2019d purchased at a sporting goods store in Philadelphia for $37.50, and secured it with two clips and 33 loose cartridges.}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[1982 Wilkes-Barre Shootings|Wilkes-Barre shootings]] || 1982 || [[Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania]] || 13 || 1 || Semi-automatic rifle || <ref>{{cite court |plaintiffs=Banks v. Horn |court=[[United States Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit]]|opinion=99-9005|date=October 31, 2001 |authorlink=[[Midge Rendell]] |first=Marjorie |last=Rendell |quote=On September 25, 1982 in Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania, Banks shot fourteen people with a Colt AR-15 semi-automatic rifle, killing thirteen and wounding one. |url=https://caselaw.findlaw.com/us-3rd-circuit/1402418.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite court |quote=In the space of about one hour, appellant shot fourteen people with a Colt AR-15 semi-automatic rifle, killing thirteen and wounding one. |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/pennsylvania/supreme-court/1987/513-pa-318-1.html |court=[[Supreme Court of Pennsylvania]] |year=1987 |vol=513 |reporter=Pa. |opinion=318}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Dietz |first=P.E. |year=1986 |title=Mass, serial and sensational homicides |journal=[[Journal of Urban Health|Bulletin of the New York Academy of Medicine]] |volume=62 |number=5 |pages=477\u2013491 |quote=He had purchased equipment and materials of the kind advertised and promoted in these magazines, including a Colt AR-15 semi-automatic rifle... |pmc=1629267|pmid=3461857 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Wah Mee massacre]] || 1983 || [[Seattle, Washington]] || 13 || 1 || Semi-automatic pistol(s) and/or revolver(s)<ref group=\"fn\" name=\"wah mee\">During the massacre, the perpetrators used three [[.22 caliber]] handguns of an unknown type which were never recovered by the authorities.</ref> || <ref name=\"Wah Mee massacre\">{{cite web|last=Kang|first=Martha|title=Wah Mee Massacre prisoner closer to release|url=http://komonews.com/news/local/wah-mee-massacre-prisoner-closer-to-release|publisher=[[KOMO-TV|KOMO News]]|date=February 26, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Columbine High School massacre]] || 1999 || [[Columbine, Colorado]] || 13 <small>(plus 2 perps.)</small> || 24 (21 from gunfire) || Semi-automatic carbine, semi-automatic pistol, shotguns ||<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2016/02/24/columbine-killer-has-cult-of-fans-long-after-death/|title=Columbine killer has cult of fans long after death|date=February 24, 2016|work=[[New York Post]]|accessdate=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Binghamton shootings]] || 2009 || [[Binghamton, New York]] |