 shading/Democratic}}|'''55.6%''' ''1,739''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|2.2% ''69''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1892 United States presidential election|1892]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|40.7% ''1,112''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''52.3%''' ''1,428''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|7.1% ''193''\n|}\n{{Hidden end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Illinois#Wabash County|National Register of Historic Places listings in Wabash County]]\n* [[Grand Rapids Hotel]]\n* [[Grand Rapids Dam]]\n* [[Hanging Rock (Wabash River)]]\n* [[Charles T. Hinde]]\n* [[Thomas S. Hinde]]\n* [[Frederick Hinde Zimmerman]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Geographic Location\n|Centre    = Wabash County, Illinois\n|North     = [[Lawrence County, Illinois|Lawrence County]]\n|Northeast = [[Knox County, Indiana]]\n|East      = [[Gibson County, Indiana]]\n|Southeast =\n|South     = [[White County, Illinois|White County]]\n|Southwest =\n|West      = [[Edwards County, Illinois|Edwards County]]\n|Northwest = [[Richland County, Illinois|Richland County]]\n}}\n{{Wabash County, Illinois}}\n{{Illinois}}\n{{Southern-Illinois |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Illinois counties]]\n[[Category:Wabash County, Illinois| ]]\n[[Category:Little Egypt|Wabash County, Illinois]]\n[[Category:1824 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1824]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|County in Illinois}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox U.S. county\n| county = Wabash County\n| state = Illinois\n| seal = \n| founded = 1824\n| seat wl= Mount Carmel\n| largest city wl= Mount Carmel\n| coordinates = {{coord|38.44|-87.84|display=inline, title|type:adm2nd_region:US-IL_source:UScensus1990}}\n| area_total_sq_mi = 228\n| area_land_sq_mi = 223\n| area_water_sq_mi = 4.3\n| area percentage = 1.9\n| population_as_of = 2010\n| population_total = 11947\n| pop_est_as_of = 2018\n| population_est = 11549\n| population_density_sq_mi = auto\n| time zone = Central\n| footnotes = \n| web = \n| ex image = Wabash County Courthouse in Mount Carmel.jpg\n| ex image cap = The [[Wabash County Courthouse (Illinois)|county courthouse]] in Mount Carmel\n| district = 15th\n| named for = [[Wabash River]]\n}}\n[[File:Mount Carmel Cherry St.JPG|thumb|right|Cherry St. in Mount Carmel, still paved in brick, is home to many interesting examples of around the start of the 20th century architecture]]\n\n'''Wabash County''' is a [[County (United States)|county]] located in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Illinois]]. According to the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]], it had a population of 11,947.<ref name=\"QF\">{{cite web|title=State & County QuickFacts|url=http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/17/17185.html|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 9, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714164655/http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/17/17185.html|archivedate=July 14, 2014}}</ref> Its [[county seat]] is [[Mount Carmel, Illinois|Mount Carmel]].<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx|accessdate=2011-06-07|title=Find a County|publisher=National Association of Counties}}</ref> It is located in the southern portion of Illinois known locally as \"[[Little Egypt (region)|Little Egypt]]\".\n\n==History==\nWabash County was formed in 1824 out of [[Edwards County, Illinois|Edwards County]], to avert an armed confrontation between the militias of [[Albion, Illinois|Albion]] and [[Mount Carmel, Illinois|Mt. Carmel]] after the county seat was moved from a town near the current city of Mount Carmel to Albion.\n\nThe County is named for the [[Wabash River]], which forms its eastern and southern borders. The name \"Wabash\" is an English spelling of the French name for the river, \"Ouabache.\" French traders named the river after the [[Miami (tribe)|Miami Indian]] word for the river, \"Wabashike,\" (pronounced \"Wah-bah-she-keh\"), the word for \"pure white.\" Much of the river bottom is white limestone, now obscured by mud.\n<gallery>\nFile:Wabash County Illinois 1824.png|Wabash County at the time of its creation in 1824\n</gallery>\n\nA {{convert|329|acre|km2}} remnant of the county's original Eastern Woodlands [[ecosystem]] can be found in the ''Forest of the Wabash'' located within the county's [[Beall Woods State Park]].\n\nIn the 1920s there existed a famous hotel and resort that existed in Wabash County nearby the Grand Rapids Dam on the Wabash River.  The hotel was named the [[Grand Rapids Hotel]] and was owned by [[Frederick Hinde Zimmerman]].  During the hotel's nine-year existence it catered to individuals from all over the United States.  In July 2011, John Matthew Nolan wrote a detailed history of the [[Grand Rapids Hotel]].\n\n===Earthquake===\n{{main|2008 Illinois earthquake}}\nOn the morning of April 18, 2008, at 4:37am local time, one of the largest earthquakes in Illinois history hit the area. The epicenter of this tremor was in Lick Prairie Township, near the middle of the county. The tremor was felt more than 400 miles away in Nebraska.<ref name=\"SuhrSFChron\">{{cite web |url= http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/n/a/2008/04/18/national/a025745D02.DTL |title= 5.2 earthquake rattles skyscrapers, nerves across Midwest |author= Jim Suhr, [[Associated Press]] |work= [[San Francisco Chronicle]] |date= April 18, 2008 |quote= It was the kind of tremor that might be ignored in earthquake-savvy California, but the temblor shook things up from [[Nebraska]] to Atlanta and rattled nerves in [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin|Milwaukee]], [[Cincinnati, Ohio|Cincinnati]] and [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville, Ky.]], where bricks toppled to the pavement... Dozens of [[aftershock]]s followed, including one with a magnitude of 4.6. }}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n[[Image:Mount Carmel bridge 2007.JPG|thumb|right|Bridge on [[Illinois Route 15]] connecting Wabash and [[Gibson County, Indiana|Gibson]] counties. This span no longer exists.]]\n\nAccording to the [[U.S. Census Bureau]], the county has a total area of {{convert|228|sqmi}}, of which {{convert|223|sqmi}} is land and {{convert|4.3|sqmi}} (1.9%) is water.<ref name=\"census-density\"/> It is the fifth-smallest county in Illinois by area.\n\n===Climate and weather===\n{{climate chart\n|[[Mount Carmel, Illinois]]\n|21|38|2.90\n|25|44|2.73\n|35|54|4.15\n|44|66|4.24\n|54|76|5.12\n|63|85|3.70\n|67|89|4.24\n|65|87|3.61\n|57|81|2.80\n|45|70|3.03\n|36|55|4.19\n|25|43|3.05\n|float=right\n|units=imperial\n|clear=both\n|source=The Weather Channel<ref name=\"weather\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.weather.com/weather/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/USIL0807\n  |title=Monthly Averages for Mount Carmel, Illinois\n  |accessdate=2011-01-27\n  |publisher=The Weather Channel\n}}</ref>}}\nIn recent years, average temperatures in the county seat of Mount Carmel have ranged from a low of {{convert|21|\u00b0F}} in January to a high of {{convert|89|\u00b0F}} in July, although a record low of {{convert|-19|\u00b0F}} was recorded in January 1985 and a record high of {{convert|102|\u00b0F}} was recorded in July 1988.  Average monthly precipitation ranged from {{convert|2.73|in}} in February to {{convert|5.12|in}} in May.<ref name=\"weather\"/>\n\n===Major highways===\n*[[Image:Illinois 1.svg|20px]] [[Illinois Route 1]]\n*[[Image:Illinois 15.svg|20px]] [[Illinois Route 15]]\n\n===Adjacent counties===\n*[[Lawrence County, Illinois|Lawrence County]] - north\n*[[Knox County, Indiana]] - northeast\n*[[Gibson County, Indiana]] - south and mostly east\n*[[Edwards County, Illinois|Edwards County]] - west\n*[[Richland County, Illinois|Richland County]] - northwest\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1830= 2710\n|1840= 4240\n|1850= 4690\n|1860= 7313\n|1870= 8841\n|1880= 9945\n|1890= 11866\n|1900= 12583\n|1910= 14913\n|1920= 14034\n|1930= 13197\n|1940= 13724\n|1950= 14651\n|1960= 14047\n|1970= 12841\n|1980= 13713\n|1990= 13111\n|2000= 12937\n|2010= 11947\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=11549\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=November 2, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 9, 2014}}</ref><br />1790-1960<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu|title=Historical Census Browser|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=July 9, 2014}}</ref> 1900-1990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/il190090.txt|title=Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 9, 2014}}</ref><br />1990-2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|title=Census 2000 PHC-T-4. Ranking Tables for Counties: 1990 and 2000|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 9, 2014}}</ref> 2010-2013<ref name=\"QF\"/>\n}}\n\nAs of the [[2010 United States Census]], there were 11,947&nbsp;people, 5,012&nbsp;households, and 3,310&nbsp;families residing in the county.<ref name=\"census-dp1\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/0500000US17185\n  |title=DP-1 Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 Demographic Profile Data\n  |accessdate=2015-07-12\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213020341/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/0500000US17185\n  |archive-date=February 13, 2020\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref> The population density was {{convert|53.5|PD/sqmi}}. There were 5,585 housing units at an average density of {{convert|25.0|/sqmi}}.<ref name=\"census-density\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US17185\n  |accessdate=2015-07-12\n  |title=Population, Housing Units, Area, and Density: 2010 - County\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213192318/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US17185\n  |archive-date=February 13, 2020\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref> The racial makeup of the county was 96.9% white, 0.6% black or African American, 0.6% Asian, 0.2% American Indian, 0.5% from other races, and 1.1% from two or more races. Those of Hispanic or Latino origin made up 1.3% of the population.<ref name=\"census-dp1\"/> In terms of ancestry, 25.6% were [[Germans|German]], 12.3% were [[English people|English]], 11.7% were [[Americans|American]], and 8.4% were [[Irish people|Irish]].<ref name=\"census-dp2\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0500000US17185\n  |title=DP02 SELECTED SOCIAL CHARACTERISTICS IN THE UNITED STATES \u2013 2006-2010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates\n  |accessdate=2015-07-12\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213034159/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0500000US17185\n  |archive-date=February 13, 2020\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref>\n\nOf the 5,012&nbsp;households, 29.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 52.9% were married couples living together, 9.3% had a female householder with no husband present, 34.0% were non-families, and 29.4% of all households were made up of individuals. The average household size was 2.37 and the average family size was 2.91. The median age was 42.0 years.<ref name=\"census-dp1\"/>\n\nThe median income for a household in the county was $46,026 and the median income for a family was $55,611. Males had a median income of $44,932 versus $28,292 for females. The per capita income for the county was $23,350. About 7.2% of families and 13.0% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 12.2% of those under age 18 and 8.6% of those age 65 or over.<ref name=\"census-dp3\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP03/0500000US17185\n  |title=DP03 SELECTED ECONOMIC CHARACTERISTICS \u2013 2006-2010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates\n  |accessdate=2015-07-12\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213025712/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP03/0500000US17185\n  |archive-date=February 13, 2020\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref>\n\n==Communities==\n\n===Cities===\n*[[Mount Carmel, Illinois|Mount Carmel]]\n\n===Villages===\n*[[Allendale, Illinois|Allendale]]\n*[[Bellmont, Illinois|Bellmont]]\n*[[Keensburg, Illinois|Keensburg]]\n\n===Unincorporated communities===\n*[[Cowling, Illinois|Cowling]]\n*[[Friendsville, Illinois|Friendsville]]\n*[[Lancaster, Illinois|Lancaster]]\n*[[Maud, Illinois|Maud]]\n*[[Odgen, Illinois|Odgen]]\n\n===Precincts===\nWabash County is one of 17 Illinois counties that use the term [[List of precincts in Illinois|precinct]].\n\n[[Image:Wabash County, IL.png|thumb|right|Precincts of Wabash County|250px]]\n* [[Bellmont Precinct, Wabash County, Illinois|Bellmont]] (Bellmont)\n* [[Coffee Precinct, Wabash County, Illinois|Coffee]] (Keensburg)\n* [[Compton Precinct, Wabash County, Illinois|Compton]] (East Grayville)\n* [[Friendsville Precinct, Wabash County, Illinois|Friendsville]] (Friendsville)\n* [[Lancaster Precinct, Wabash County, Illinois|Lancaster]] (Lancaster)\n* [[Lick Prairie Precinct, Wabash County, Illinois|Lick Prairie]] (Lick Prairie)\n* [[Mount Carmel Precinct, Wabash County, Illinois|Mount Carmel]] (Mount Carmel)\n* [[Wabash Precinct, Wabash County, Illinois|Wabash]] (Allendale)\n\n[https://web.archive.org/web/20071020170142/http://www.cyberdriveillinois.com/departments/archives/irad/wabash.html Wabash County precincts and their boundaries]\n\n==Politics==\n{{Hidden begin\n|titlestyle = background:#ccccff;\n|title      = Presidential elections results\n}}\n{| align=\"center\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"float:right; margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+ '''Presidential elections results'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS|title=Dave Leip's Atlas of U.S. Presidential Elections|last=Leip|first=David|website=uselectionatlas.org|access-date=2018-11-13}}</ref>\n|- bgcolor=lightgrey\n! Year\n! [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n! [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n! [[Third Party (United States)|Third parties]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[2016 United States presidential election|2016]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''74.1%''' ''4,047''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|21.1% ''1,151''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|4.9% ''266''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[2012 United States presidential election|2012]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''67.7%''' ''3,478''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|31.0% ''1,590''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|1.3% ''66''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[2008 United States presidential election|2008]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''56.2%''' ''3,254''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|42.5% ''2,462''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|1.4% ''78''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[2004 United St