{"title_page": "Lida Moser", "text_new": "<br />\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Lida Moser\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1920|8|17|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York City]], New York\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2014|8|11|1920|8|17}}\n| death_place        = [[Rockville, MD]]\n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = \n| occupation         = [[Photographer]], [[author]]\n| years_active       = 1947 &mdash; 2014\n| employer           = \n| known_for          = photojournalism, portraiture, fashion, experimental, street photography\n| notable_works      = Judy and the Boys, 1961\n| spouse             = \n| partner            = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| awards             = \n| website            = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n'''Lida Moser''' (August 17, 1920 \u2013 August 11, 2014)<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> was an American-born [[photographer]] and [[author]], with a career that spanned more than six decades, before retiring in her 90s. She was known for her photojournalism and [[street photography]] as a member of both the [[Photo League]] <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.higherpictures.com/artists/Women_of_the_Photo_League/Works.aspx?s=190 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-09-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120103043632/http://www.higherpictures.com/artists/Women_of_the_Photo_League/Works.aspx?s=190 |archivedate=2012-01-03 }} | Women of the Photo League</ref> and the New York School. Her portfolio includes black and white commercial, portrait, landscape, experimental, [[Abstraction|abstract,]] and [[documentary photography]], with her work continuing to have an impact.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe Photo League was an early center of American documentary photography in the post war years, with membership including many of the most significant photographers of the 20th century. In a retrospective at the [[Fraser Gallery]] in Washington DC, she was described as a pioneer in the field of photojournalism,<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefrasergallery.com/reviews/LidaMoserWCP2005.html |title=Lida Moser: Fifty Years of Photographs|first=Louis |last=Jacobson |date=8 April 2005 |work=Washington City Paper |accessdate=2012-09-21}}</ref>  and ''The [[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' noted that she \"excelled at photojournalism at a time when women were a rarity in the field.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Slotnik|first=Daniel E.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/03/arts/lida-moser-photographer-with-an-urban-eye-dies-at-93.html|title=Lida Moser, Photographer With an Urban Eye, Dies at 93|date=2014-09-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> She has also been described, much to Moser's annoyance,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/arts/museums-galleries/blog/13081071/why-photographer-lida-moser-couldnt-be-pigeonholed|title=Why Photographer Lida Moser Couldn't Be Pigeonholed|website=Washington City Paper|language=en|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref> the ''\"grandmother of American photojournalism.\"''<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/arts/article/13028481/photographic-memories|title=Photographic Memories|last=Summers-Sparks|first=Matthew|date=2004-02-20|website=Washington City Paper|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMoser was born in 1920 in New York City.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/lida-moser-photographer-of-new-york-and-beyond-dies-at-93/2014/08/30/ea3fb98a-2ec3-11e4-9b98-848790384093_story.html|title=Lida Moser, photographer of New York and beyond, dies at 93|author=Emily Langer|date=August 30, 2014|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Moser|first=Lidia|title=United States Public Records Index|url=https://familysearch.org|publisher=Family Search|accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref> Her career started in 1947 as an assistant in [[Berenice Abbott|Berenice Abbott's]] studio.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/local-news/photojournalist-made-her-mark-in-quebec/|title=Photojournalist made her mark in Quebec|last=Lalonde|first=Michelle|date=2014-04-14|website=The Montreal Gazette|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> She then earned her first assignment from ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' in 1949, traveling to [[Scotland]] and then across [[Canada|Canada.]] Other magazines subsequently featuring her work included ''[[Harper's Bazaar]]'', ''[[Look (American magazine)|Look]],'' ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]],'' and others. She authored a number of books of her own work ,and co-authored several photographic technique books. Articles and ongoing columns appeared also in the ''New York Times'', ''New York Sunday Times'', ''Amphoto Guide to Special Effects'', ''Fun in Photography'', ''Career Photography'', ''Women See Men'', ''Women of Vision'' and ''This Was the Photo League'', among others.\n\nMoser\u2019s series of \"Camera View\" articles on photography for ''The New York Times'' appeared between 1974 and 1981.<ref name=\"cooperative galleries3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefrasergallery.com/reviews/LidaMoserWCP2005.html|title=A Photographer's Guide to Cooperative Galleries; Cooperative Galleries|last=Moser|first=Lida|date=17 October 1976|work=New York Times|accessdate=2012-09-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artforum.com/news/lida-moser-1920-2014-48110|title=Lida Moser (1920\u20132014)|website=www.artforum.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> Her photography has fetched as much as $4,000 at Christie's and other auctions<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artnet.com/artists/lida-moser/past-auction-results|title=Past Auction Results for Lida Moser|website=Artnet.com|accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref> and continues to be collected and displayed by more than 40 museums worldwide.<ref name=\"NGS3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/search?search=Lida%20Moser|title=Artworks, 115 artworks, Lida Moser|website=National Galleries Scotland|accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref> Moser\u2019s relationship to French photographer [[Eug\u00e8ne Atget]] can be seen in her photographs of [[Edinburgh]] as an early influence and that of American photographer [[Walker Evans]].\n\nMoser was a close friend of American artist [[Alice Neel]], and she photographed Neel several times;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bangordailynews.com/2014/09/02/living/noted-photographer-lida-moser-dies-at-93/|title=Noted photographer Lida Moser dies at 93|website=Bangor Daily News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> in return Neel painted multiple portraits of Moser, which now hang is several museums in the U.S.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/484558|title=''Lida Moser'' 1963, Alice Neel|website=www.metmuseum.org|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Scotland ===\nIn 1949 Moser was assigned by ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' magazine to travel to Scotland and photograph leading [[List of Scottish writers|Scottish writers]] and artists. Over 100 of those photographs are now in the permanent collection of [[National Galleries of Scotland|The National Galleries of Scotland]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/search|title=Artworks {{!}} National Galleries of Scotland - Lida Moser Search|last=|first=|date=|website=www.nationalgalleries.org|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Moser photographed key artists and writers such as [[James Bridie|James Birdie]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108702/james-bridie|title=James Bridie|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> [[Stanley Cursiter]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108703/stanley-cursiter-1887-1976-artist-his-studio|title=Stanley Cursiter, 1887 - 1976. Artist in his Studio|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> [[William Crosbie (artist)|William Crosbie]],<ref name=\":5\" /> [[Hugh MacDiarmid]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108631/christopher-murray-grieve-nom-de-plume-hugh-macdiarmid-1892-1978-poet|title=Christopher Murray Grieve (nom de plume 'Hugh MacDiarmid'), 1892 - 1978. Poet|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> [[Sorley MacLean]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108636/sorley-maclean-1911-1996-poet|title=Sorley MacLean, 1911 - 1996. Poet|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>[[Anne Redpath]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108640/anne-redpath-1895-1965-artist|title=Anne Redpath, 1895 - 1965. Artist|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> [[Benno Schotz]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108652/benno-schotz-1891-1984-sculptor|title=Benno Schotz, 1891 - 1984. Sculptor|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> [[Douglas Young (classicist)|Douglas Young]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108664/douglas-young-1913-1973-poet|title=Douglas Young, 1913 - 1973. Poet|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>  and many others.\n\n=== Canada ===\n''Vogue'' was so pleased with the result of Moser's work in Scotland, that a year later, in 1950, they assigned the young photographer an even more ambitious task: to visit the Canadian province of [[Quebec]] and deliver a photographic essay on Quebec.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.westmountmag.ca/lida-moser/|title=Lida Moser\u2019s homage to \u201cla belle province\u201d|date=2018-04-08|website=Westmount Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" />During the summer of that year, \"Moser travelled all along the St. Laurence River, from Montreal to Quebec City, then on to Charlevoix, the lower Saint-Lawrence and the Gasp\u00e9 peninsula.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> She then returned later in 1950, this time under assignment by [[Look (American magazine)|''Look'']] magazine, to photograph \"the inhabitants \u2013 everyday people, children, artists, storytellers, actors, lovers and more.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> A documentary of her Canadian travels and photographs was written and directed by Joyce Borenstein ,and was released in 2017 under the title ''Lida Moser Photographer: Odyssey in Black and White''.<ref>{{Citation|title=Lida Moser Photographer: Odyssey in Black and White|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6599250/|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.musee-mccord.qc.ca/en/activities/screening-lida-moser-photographer/|title=Screening of Lida Moser Photographer - McCord Museum|website=Musee McCord|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Judy and the Boys ===\n[[File:Judy and the Boys 1961.jpg|300px|thumb| \"Judy and the Boys (Mimicry)\" Photograph by Lida Moser, 1961.]]\nAccording to ''The New York Times'', \"Perhaps her most famous photograph, \u201cMimicry ([[:File:Judy and the Boys 1961.jpg|Judy and the Boys]])\u201d (1961), began as a shoot for an aspiring model. Ms. Moser had posed her in front of a Greenwich Village garage when some neighborhood children demanded to be in the picture, then they began mimicking the model\u2019s poses. The model responded with a crude gesture, captured by Ms. Moser.\"<ref name=\":2\" /> In discussing the same photograph, [[Washington City Paper|''The Washington City Paper'']] wrote: \"The piece typifies Moser\u2019s work: It captures a moment in which people have let their guard down and are acting genuinely, features details of a long-vanished New York, and clearly displays the empathy Moser felt toward her subjects.\"<ref name=\":9\" /> The Library of Congress purchased one of the original vintage prints in 1998.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nMoser died on August 11, 2014, in Rockville, Maryland, six days shy of her 94th birthday.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=http://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/arts_et_spectacles/2014/08/13/009-deces-de-la-photographe-lida-moser.shtml|title=Deces de Lida Moser photographe du Quebic desannees 1950|year=2014|author=Sophie Cazenave|website=Radio Canada|access-date=March 25, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Permanent collections==\n\nMoser's work is in the permanent collection of:\n\n*[[Museum of Modern Art]], [[New York City|New York]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moma.org/artists/49613|title=Lida Moser {{!}} MoMA|website=The Museum of Modern Art|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*A portrait of Moser, by painter [[Alice Neel]], is in the permanent collection of the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in New York City.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/484558|title=''Lida Moser'' 1963, Alice Neel| website=www.metmuseum.org|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*[[Corcoran Gallery]], Washington, DC\n*[[Phillips Collection]], Washington, DC<ref name=\":3\" />\n*[[Biblioth\u00e8que et Archives nationales du Qu\u00e9bec]], [[Quebec City|Quebec]], Canada<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://lidamoser.mnbaq.org/|title=Le qu\u00e9bec de Lida Moser|last=|first=|date=|website=Biblioth\u00e8que et Archives nationales du Qu\u00e9bec|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lidamoser.mnbaq.org/biographie/|title=La photographe Lida Moser \u2022 Le qu\u00e9bec de Lida Moser|website=Le qu\u00e9bec de Lida Moser|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconcordian.com/2016/02/the-1950s-in-quebec-through-the-eyes-of-lida-moser/|title=The 1950s in Quebec through the eyes of Lida Moser|last=Sachet|first=Ambre|date=2016-02-02|website=The Concordian|language=en-CA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n*[[Library of Congress]], Washington, DC<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/photos/?q=lida+moser|title=Search results for Photo, Print, Drawing, Lida Moser, Available Online|website=Library of Congress, Washington, D.C. 20540 USA|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[Library and Archives Canada]], [[Ottawa]], Canada<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/news/archive/2015/05/something-old-something-new-access-heart-lac-mandate.html|title=Something old, something new: access and the heart of LAC's mandate|last=Canada|first=Service|date=2015-05-12|website=gcnws|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n*[[National Galleries of Scotland]], [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]]<ref name=\"NGS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/search?search=Lida%20Moser|title=Artworks, 115 artworks, Lida Moser|website=National Galleries Scotland|accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[National Portrait Gallery, London]], [[United Kingdom]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp08538/lida-moser |title=Search the Collection Lida Moser (1920-2014)|website= National Portrait Gallery London|access-date=March 25, 2019}}</ref> \n*[[National Portrait Gallery (United States)|National Portrait Gallery]], Washington, DC<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://npg.si.edu/object/npg_NPG.2016.134|title=Judy Collins|website=npg.si.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n*[[New-York Historical Society|New York Historical Society]], New York <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/nyhs/moser/|title=Guide to the Lida Moser Photograph Collection New York Historical Society|website=dlib.nyu.edu|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref>\n*[[Smithsonian Institution]], Washington, DC <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://collections.si.edu/search/results.htm?q=lida%20moser|title=Collections Search Center, Smithsonian Institution|website=collections.si.edu|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref>\n*[[Museum of Fine Arts, Houston|Museum of Fine Arts]], [[Houston]], [[Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://emuseum.mfah.org/objects/26917/aaron-siskind|title=Aaron Siskind Photograph by Lida Moser|last=|first=|date=|website=The Museum of Fine Arts Houston|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n*[[Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art]], [[Bentonville, Arkansas|Bentonville]], [[Arkansas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://crystalbridges.org/blog/womens-history-month-lida-moser/|title=Women\u2019s History Month: Lida Moser|date=2016-03-09|website=Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n*[[Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art]], [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]], [[Missouri]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://localhost/people/10644/lida-moser;jsessionid=9EA69A7E21C8959021F2E907F2FE3959|title=Lida Moser \u2013 Artists/Makers \u2013 The Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art|website=localhost|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n*[[Ryerson Image Centre]], [[Toronto]], Canada<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ryersonimagecentre.ca/news/december-2-2019-the-ric-acquires-nearly-500-photographic-masterpieces-from-howard-and-carole-tanenbaums-private-collection/|title=The RIC acquires nearly 500 photographic masterpieces from Howard and Carole Tanenbaum\u2019s private collection {{!}} Ryerson Image Centre|website=ryersonimagecentre.ca|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n*Trout Gallery at [[Dickinson College|Dickinson Colleg]]<nowiki/>e, [[Carlisle, Pennsylvania|Carlisle]], [[Pennsylvania]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.troutgallery.org/exhibitions/past/2017-2018/|title=The Trout Gallery|website=www.troutgallery.org|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Significant works==\n\n*1949 \"Queen's Parade, Edinburgh, Scotland\"<ref name=\"gallery work\" />\n*1949 \"John Boyd Orr, Baron Boyd Orr\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/portrait/mw09875/John-Boyd-Orr-Baron-Boyd-Orr|title=John Boyd Orr, Baron Boyd Orr - National Portrait Gallery|website=www.npg.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*1949 \"Douglas Young\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/portrait/mw09876/Douglas-Young|title=Douglas Young - National Portrait Gallery|website=www.npg.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*1949 \"Stanley Cursiter\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/artists/lida-moser|title=Lida Moser {{!}} National Galleries of Scotland|website=www.nationalgalleries.org|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*1949 \"Dovecot Studios, Edinburgh Tapestry Company\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/10141/dovecot-studios-edinburgh-tapestry-company-ronnie-mcvinnie-john-loufit-fred-marin-richard-gordon|title=Dovecot Studios, Edinburgh Tapestry Company (Ronnie McVinnie, John Loufit, Fred Marin, Richard Gordon, Alec Jack, Ian Inglis, Archie Brennan,...|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*1950 \"Farm Girls, Valley of the Matapedia, Quebec\"<ref name=\"gallery work\" />\n*1950 \"Two students of Quebec City's Ecole Moderne pose with sculptures\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconcordian.com/2016/02/the-1950s-in-quebec-through-the-eyes-of-lida-moser/|title=The 1950s in Quebec through the eyes of Lida Moser|date=2016-02-02|website=The Concordian|language=en-CA|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*1961 \"Judy and the Boys\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.loc.gov/pictures/item/98517055/|title=Mimicry (Judy and the boys)|last=Moser|first=Lida|date=1961|website=www.loc.gov|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*1965 \"Office Bldg. Lobby, New York\"<ref name=\"gallery work\" />\n*1968 \"Cops, Times Square, New York\"<ref name=\"gallery work\" />\n*1971 \"Construction of the Exxon Building, New York'<ref name=\"NGS\" /><ref name=\"gallery work\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A62979-2005Mar24.html |title=Lida Moser At Her Finest|work=The Washington Post |accessdate=2012-09-21 |first=Michael |last=O'Sullivan |date=March 25, 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n\n*Earthman, Come Home (1966)\n*A Life For the Stars (Cities in Flight, 2) (Avon SF, G1280) (1968)\n*Construction of the Exxon Building, New York (1971)\n*Fun in Photography Amphoto U.S.(1974) {{ISBN|978-0-8174-056-49}}\n*Amphoto Guide to Special Effects Watson-Guptill Pubns(1980) {{ISBN|978-0-8174-352-40}}\n*'Photography Contests: How to Enter, How to Win Amphoto U.S.(1981){{ISBN|978-0-8174-244-59}}\n*Grants in Photography: How to Get Them (1979){{ISBN|978-0-8174-244-59}}\n*Quebec a l'ete 1950 Libre Expression (French Edition) (1982) {{ISBN|978-2-8911-111-02}}\n*Career Photography: How to Be a Success As a Professional Photographer Prentice Hall Trade (1983){{ISBN|978-0-13115-11-30}} <ref>{{cite news |url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0A1EF8355A1A7493C5A8178BD95F428785F9&scp=1&sq=A%20Photographer%27s%20Guide%20to%20Cooperative%20Galleries&st=cse# |title=Lida Moser Amazon Bibliography |work=Amazon.com | date=October 17, 1976}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nMoser's 1971 book  \u201c''Construction of Exxon Building, New York City\"'' features a photo of window washers that has been recreated in Lego building blocks at [[Legoland Miniland New York City|Legoland Florida]] theme park.\n\n''Office Building Lobby, New York'', in which Moser\u2019s wild overexposure has reduced organization men to near\u2013stick figures and the lobby to an ill-defined blob, presaging by several years the visual distortions of [[2001: A Space Odyssey]].<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/03/arts/lida-moser-photographer-with-an-urban-eye-dies-at-93.html Lida Moser obituary in ''The New York Times'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moser, Lida}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:American photographers]]\n[[Category:American women photographers]]\n[[Category:Photographers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Photographers from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Photographers from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Artists from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Jewish American artists]]\n[[Category:Street photographers]]\n", "text_old": "<br />\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Lida Moser\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1920|8|17|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York City]], New York\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2014|8|11|1920|8|17}}\n| death_place        = [[Rockville, MD]]\n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = \n| occupation         = [[Photographer]], [[author]]\n| years_active       = 1947 &mdash; 2014\n| employer           = \n| known_for          = photojournalism, portraiture, fashion, experimental, street photography\n| notable_works      = Judy and the Boys, 1961\n| spouse             = \n| partner            = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| awards             = \n| website            = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n'''Lida Moser''' (August 17, 1920 \u2013 August 11, 2014)<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> was an American-born [[photographer]] and [[author]], with a career that spanned more than six decades, before retiring in her 90s. She was known for her photojournalism and [[street photography]] as a member of both the [[Photo League]] <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.higherpictures.com/artists/Women_of_the_Photo_League/Works.aspx?s=190 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-09-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120103043632/http://www.higherpictures.com/artists/Women_of_the_Photo_League/Works.aspx?s=190 |archivedate=2012-01-03 }} | Women of the Photo League</ref> and the New York School. Her portfolio includes black and white commercial, portrait, landscape, experimental, [[Abstraction|abstract,]] and [[documentary photography]], with her work continuing to have an impact.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe Photo League was an early center of American documentary photography in the post war years, with membership including many of the most significant photographers of the 20th century. In a retrospective at the [[Fraser Gallery]] in Washington DC, she was described as a pioneer in the field of photojournalism,<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefrasergallery.com/reviews/LidaMoserWCP2005.html |title=Lida Moser: Fifty Years of Photographs|first=Louis |last=Jacobson |date=8 April 2005 |work=Washington City Paper |accessdate=2012-09-21}}</ref>  and ''The [[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' noted that she \"excelled at photojournalism at a time when women were a rarity in the field.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Slotnik|first=Daniel E.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/03/arts/lida-moser-photographer-with-an-urban-eye-dies-at-93.html|title=Lida Moser, Photographer With an Urban Eye, Dies at 93|date=2014-09-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> She has also been described, much to Moser's annoyance,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/arts/museums-galleries/blog/13081071/why-photographer-lida-moser-couldnt-be-pigeonholed|title=Why Photographer Lida Moser Couldn't Be Pigeonholed|website=Washington City Paper|language=en|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref> the ''\"grandmother of American photojournalism.\"''<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/arts/article/13028481/photographic-memories|title=Photographic Memories|last=Summers-Sparks|first=Matthew|date=2004-02-20|website=Washington City Paper|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMoser was born in 1920 in New York City.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/lida-moser-photographer-of-new-york-and-beyond-dies-at-93/2014/08/30/ea3fb98a-2ec3-11e4-9b98-848790384093_story.html|title=Lida Moser, photographer of New York and beyond, dies at 93|author=Emily Langer|date=August 30, 2014|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Moser|first=Lidia|title=United States Public Records Index|url=https://familysearch.org|publisher=Family Search|accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref> Her career started in 1947 as an assistant in [[Berenice Abbott|Berenice Abbott's]] studio.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/local-news/photojournalist-made-her-mark-in-quebec/|title=Photojournalist made her mark in Quebec|last=Lalonde|first=Michelle|date=2014-04-14|website=The Montreal Gazette|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> She then earned her first assignment from ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' in 1949, traveling to [[Scotland]] and then across [[Canada|Canada.]] Other magazines subsequently featuring her work included ''[[Harper's Bazaar]]'', ''[[Look (American magazine)|Look]],'' ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]],'' and others. She authored a number of books of her own work ,and co-authored several photographic technique books. Articles and ongoing columns appeared also in the ''New York Times'', ''New York Sunday Times'', ''Amphoto Guide to Special Effects'', ''Fun in Photography'', ''Career Photography'', ''Women See Men'', ''Women of Vision'' and ''This Was the Photo League'', among others.\n\nMoser\u2019s series of \"Camera View\" articles on photography for ''The New York Times'' appeared between 1974 and 1981.<ref name=\"cooperative galleries3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefrasergallery.com/reviews/LidaMoserWCP2005.html|title=A Photographer's Guide to Cooperative Galleries; Cooperative Galleries|last=Moser|first=Lida|date=17 October 1976|work=New York Times|accessdate=2012-09-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artforum.com/news/lida-moser-1920-2014-48110|title=Lida Moser (1920\u20132014)|website=www.artforum.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> Her photography has fetched as much as $4,000 at Christie's and other auctions<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artnet.com/artists/lida-moser/past-auction-results|title=Past Auction Results for Lida Moser|website=Artnet.com|accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref> and continues to be collected and displayed by more than 40 museums worldwide.<ref name=\"NGS3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/search?search=Lida%20Moser|title=Artworks, 115 artworks, Lida Moser|website=National Galleries Scotland|accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref> Moser\u2019s relationship to French photographer [[Eug\u00e8ne Atget]] can be seen in her photographs of [[Edinburgh]] as an early influence and that of American photographer [[Walker Evans]].\n\nMoser was a close friend of American artist [[Alice Neel]], and she photographed Neel several times;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bangordailynews.com/2014/09/02/living/noted-photographer-lida-moser-dies-at-93/|title=Noted photographer Lida Moser dies at 93|website=Bangor Daily News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> in return Neel painted multiple portraits of Moser, which now hang is several museums in the U.S.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/484558|title=''Lida Moser'' 1963, Alice Neel|website=www.metmuseum.org|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Scotland ===\nIn 1949 Moser was assigned by ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' magazine to travel to Scotland and photograph leading [[List of Scottish writers|Scottish writers]] and artists. Over 100 of those photographs are now in the permanent collection of [[National Galleries of Scotland|The National Galleries of Scotland]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/search|title=Artworks {{!}} National Galleries of Scotland - Lida Moser Search|last=|first=|date=|website=www.nationalgalleries.org|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Moser photographed key artists and writers such as [[James Bridie|James Birdie]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108702/james-bridie|title=James Bridie|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> [[Stanley Cursiter]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108703/stanley-cursiter-1887-1976-artist-his-studio|title=Stanley Cursiter, 1887 - 1976. Artist in his Studio|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> [[William Crosbie (artist)|William Crosbie]],<ref name=\":5\" /> [[Hugh MacDiarmid]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108631/christopher-murray-grieve-nom-de-plume-hugh-macdiarmid-1892-1978-poet|title=Christopher Murray Grieve (nom de plume 'Hugh MacDiarmid'), 1892 - 1978. Poet|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> [[Sorley MacLean]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108636/sorley-maclean-1911-1996-poet|title=Sorley MacLean, 1911 - 1996. Poet|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>[[Anne Redpath]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108640/anne-redpath-1895-1965-artist|title=Anne Redpath, 1895 - 1965. Artist|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> [[Benno Schotz]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108652/benno-schotz-1891-1984-sculptor|title=Benno Schotz, 1891 - 1984. Sculptor|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> [[Douglas Young (classicist)|Douglas Young]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108664/douglas-young-1913-1973-poet|title=Douglas Young, 1913 - 1973. Poet|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>  and many others.\n\n=== Canada ===\n''Vogue'' was so pleased with the result of Moser's work in Scotland, that a year later, in 1950, they assigned the young photographer an even more ambitious task: to visit the Canadian province of [[Quebec]] and deliver a photographic essay on Quebec.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.westmountmag.ca/lida-moser/|title=Lida Moser\u2019s homage to \u201cla belle province\u201d|date=2018-04-08|website=Westmount Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" />During the summer of that year, \"Moser travelled all along the St. Laurence River, from Montreal to Quebec City, then on to Charlevoix, the lower Saint-Lawrence and the Gasp\u00e9 peninsula.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> She then returned later in 1950, this time under assignment by [[Look (American magazine)|''Look'']] magazine, to photograph \"the inhabitants \u2013 everyday people, children, artists, storytellers, actors, lovers and more.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> A documentary of her Canadian travels and photographs was written and directed by Joyce Borenstein ,and was released in 2017 under the title ''Lida Moser Photographer: Odyssey in Black and White''.<ref>{{Citation|title=Lida Moser Photographer: Odyssey in Black and White|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6599250/|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.musee-mccord.qc.ca/en/activities/screening-lida-moser-photographer/|title=Screening of Lida Moser Photographer - McCord Museum|website=Musee McCord|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Judy and the Boys ===\n[[File:Judy and the Boys 1961.jpg|300px|thumb| \"Judy and the Boys (Mimicry)\" Photograph by Lida Moser, 1961.]]\nAccording to ''The New York Times'', \"Perhaps her most famous photograph, \u201cMimicry ([[:File:Judy and the Boys 1961.jpg|Judy and the Boys]])\u201d (1961), began as a shoot for an aspiring model. Ms. Moser had posed her in front of a Greenwich Village garage when some neighborhood children demanded to be in the picture, then they began mimicking the model\u2019s poses. The model responded with a crude gesture, captured by Ms. Moser.\"<ref name=\":2\" /> In discussing the same photograph, [[Washington City Paper|''The Washington City Paper'']] wrote: \"The piece typifies Moser\u2019s work: It captures a moment in which people have let their guard down and are acting genuinely, features details of a long-vanished New York, and clearly displays the empathy Moser felt toward her subjects.\"<ref name=\":9\" /> The Library of Congress purchased one of the original vintage prints in 1998.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nMoser died on August 11, 2014, in Rockville, Maryland, six days shy of her 94th birthday.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=http://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/arts_et_spectacles/2014/08/13/009-deces-de-la-photographe-lida-moser.shtml|title=Deces de Lida Moser photographe du Quebic desannees 1950|year=2014|author=Sophie Cazenave|website=Radio Canada|access-date=March 25, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Permanent collections==\n\nMoser's work is in the permanent collection of:\n\n*[[Museum of Modern Art]], [[New York City|New York]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moma.org/artists/49613|title=Lida Moser {{!}} MoMA|website=The Museum of Modern Art|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*A portrait of Moser, by painter [[Alice Neel]], is in the permanent collection of the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in New York City.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/484558|title=''Lida Moser'' 1963, Alice Neel| website=www.metmuseum.org|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*[[Corcoran Gallery]], Washington, DC\n*[[Phillips Collection]], Washington, DC<ref name=\":3\" />\n*[[Biblioth\u00e8que et Archives nationales du Qu\u00e9bec]], [[Quebec City|Quebec]], Canada<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://lidamoser.mnbaq.org/|title=Le qu\u00e9bec de Lida Moser|last=|first=|date=|website=Biblioth\u00e8que et Archives nationales du Qu\u00e9bec|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lidamoser.mnbaq.org/biographie/|title=La photographe Lida Moser \u2022 Le qu\u00e9bec de Lida Moser|website=Le qu\u00e9bec de Lida Moser|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconcordian.com/2016/02/the-1950s-in-quebec-through-the-eyes-of-lida-moser/|title=The 1950s in Quebec through the eyes of Lida Moser|last=Sachet|first=Ambre|date=2016-02-02|website=The Concordian|language=en-CA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n*[[Library of Congress]], Washington, DC<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/photos/?q=lida+moser|title=Search results for Photo, Print, Drawing, Lida Moser, Available Online|website=Library of Congress, Washington, D.C. 20540 USA|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[Library and Archives Canada]], [[Ottawa]], Canada<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/news/archive/2015/05/something-old-something-new-access-heart-lac-mandate.html|title=Something old, something new: access and the heart of LAC's mandate|last=Canada|first=Service|date=2015-05-12|website=gcnws|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n*[[National Galleries of Scotland]], [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]]<ref name=\"NGS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/search?search=Lida%20Moser|title=Artworks, 115 artworks, Lida Moser|website=National Galleries Scotland|accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[National Portrait Gallery, London]], [[United Kingdom]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp08538/lida-moser |title=Search the Collection Lida Moser (1920-2014)|website= National Portrait Gallery London|access-date=March 25, 2019}}</ref> \n*[[National Portrait Gallery (United States)|National Portrait Gallery]], Washington, DC<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://npg.si.edu/object/npg_NPG.2016.134|title=Judy Collins|website=npg.si.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n*[[New-York Historical Society|New York Historical Society]], New York <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/nyhs/moser/|title=Guide to the Lida Moser Photograph Collection New York Historical Society|website=dlib.nyu.edu|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref>\n*[[Smithsonian Institution]], Washington, DC <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://collections.si.edu/search/results.htm?q=lida%20moser|title=Collections Search Center, Smithsonian Institution|website=collections.si.edu|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref>\n*[[Museum of Fine Arts, Houston|Museum of Fine Arts]], [[Houston]], [[Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://emuseum.mfah.org/objects/26917/aaron-siskind|title=Aaron Siskind Photograph by Lida Moser|last=|first=|date=|website=The Museum of Fine Arts Houston|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n*[[Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art]], [[Bentonville, Arkansas|Bentonville]], [[Arkansas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://crystalbridges.org/blog/womens-history-month-lida-moser/|title=Women\u2019s History Month: Lida Moser|date=2016-03-09|website=Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n*[[Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art]], [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]], [[Missouri]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://localhost/people/10644/lida-moser;jsessionid=9EA69A7E21C8959021F2E907F2FE3959|title=Lida Moser \u2013 Artists/Makers \u2013 The Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art|website=localhost|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n*[[Ryerson Image Centre]], [[Toronto]], Canada<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ryersonimagecentre.ca/news/december-2-2019-the-ric-acquires-nearly-500-photographic-masterpieces-from-howard-and-carole-tanenbaums-private-collection/|title=The RIC acquires nearly 500 photographic masterpieces from Howard and Carole Tanenbaum\u2019s private collection {{!}} Ryerson Image Centre|website=ryersonimagecentre.ca|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Significant works==\n\n*1949 \"Queen's Parade, Edinburgh, Scotland\"<ref name=\"gallery work\" />\n*1949 \"John Boyd Orr, Baron Boyd Orr\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/portrait/mw09875/John-Boyd-Orr-Baron-Boyd-Orr|title=John Boyd Orr, Baron Boyd Orr - National Portrait Gallery|website=www.npg.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*1949 \"Douglas Young\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/portrait/mw09876/Douglas-Young|title=Douglas Young - National Portrait Gallery|website=www.npg.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*1949 \"Stanley Cursiter\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/artists/lida-moser|title=Lida Moser {{!}} National Galleries of Scotland|website=www.nationalgalleries.org|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*1949 \"Dovecot Studios, Edinburgh Tapestry Company\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/10141/dovecot-studios-edinburgh-tapestry-company-ronnie-mcvinnie-john-loufit-fred-marin-richard-gordon|title=Dovecot Studios, Edinburgh Tapestry Company (Ronnie McVinnie, John Loufit, Fred Marin, Richard Gordon, Alec Jack, Ian Inglis, Archie Brennan,...|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*1950 \"Farm Girls, Valley of the Matapedia, Quebec\"<ref name=\"gallery work\" />\n*1950 \"Two students of Quebec City's Ecole Moderne pose with sculptures\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconcordian.com/2016/02/the-1950s-in-quebec-through-the-eyes-of-lida-moser/|title=The 1950s in Quebec through the eyes of Lida Moser|date=2016-02-02|website=The Concordian|language=en-CA|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*1961 \"Judy and the Boys\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.loc.gov/pictures/item/98517055/|title=Mimicry (Judy and the boys)|last=Moser|first=Lida|date=1961|website=www.loc.gov|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*1965 \"Office Bldg. Lobby, New York\"<ref name=\"gallery work\" />\n*1968 \"Cops, Times Square, New York\"<ref name=\"gallery work\" />\n*1971 \"Construction of the Exxon Building, New York'<ref name=\"NGS\" /><ref name=\"gallery work\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A62979-2005Mar24.html |title=Lida Moser At Her Finest|work=The Washington Post |accessdate=2012-09-21 |first=Michael |last=O'Sullivan |date=March 25, 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n\n*Earthman, Come Home (1966)\n*A Life For the Stars (Cities in Flight, 2) (Avon SF, G1280) (1968)\n*Construction of the Exxon Building, New York (1971)\n*Fun in Photography Amphoto U.S.(1974) {{ISBN|978-0-8174-056-49}}\n*Amphoto Guide to Special Effects Watson-Guptill Pubns(1980) {{ISBN|978-0-8174-352-40}}\n*'Photography Contests: How to Enter, How to Win Amphoto U.S.(1981){{ISBN|978-0-8174-244-59}}\n*Grants in Photography: How to Get Them (1979){{ISBN|978-0-8174-244-59}}\n*Quebec a l'ete 1950 Libre Expression (French Edition) (1982) {{ISBN|978-2-8911-111-02}}\n*Career Photography: How to Be a Success As a Professional Photographer Prentice Hall Trade (1983){{ISBN|978-0-13115-11-30}} <ref>{{cite news |url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0A1EF8355A1A7493C5A8178BD95F428785F9&scp=1&sq=A%20Photographer%27s%20Guide%20to%20Cooperative%20Galleries&st=cse# |title=Lida Moser Amazon Bibliography |work=Amazon.com | date=October 17, 1976}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nMoser's 1971 book  \u201c''Construction of Exxon Building, New York City\"'' features a photo of window washers that has been recreated in Lego building blocks at [[Legoland Miniland New York City|Legoland Florida]] theme park.\n\n''Office Building Lobby, New York'', in which Moser\u2019s wild overexposure has reduced organization men to near\u2013stick figures and the lobby to an ill-defined blob, presaging by several years the visual distortions of [[2001: A Space Odyssey]].<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/03/arts/lida-moser-photographer-with-an-urban-eye-dies-at-93.html Lida Moser obituary in ''The New York Times'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moser, Lida}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:American photographers]]\n[[Category:American women photographers]]\n[[Category:Photographers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Photographers from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Photographers from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Artists from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Jewish American artists]]\n[[Category:Street photographers]]\n", "name_user": "BoriquaZurdo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePermanent collections", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lida_Moser"}
{"title_page": "Josh Joplin Group", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Josh Joplin Group\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| background       = Group_or_Band\n| years_active     = 1995\u20132002\n| origin           = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], United States\n| genre            = [[Alternative rock]]<br />[[Folk Rock]]<br />[[Americana music{{!}}]]<br />[[Rock music|Rock]]<br />\n| label            = [[Independent music|Independent]], SMG, [[Artemis Records|Artemis]] [[Sony]], [[Epic]]{{dn|date=April 2020}}\n| associated_acts  = \n| current_members  = \n| past_members     = [[Josh Joplin]]<br />Geoff Melkonian<br />Jason Buecker<br />Allen Broyles<br />Deeds Davis<br />[[Ani Cordero]]<br />Eric Taylor\n| website          = \n}}\n'''Josh Joplin Group''' was an Atlanta, [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]-based [[Rock music|rock]] band led by [[singer-songwriter]] [[Josh Joplin]]. Initially a trio, Joplin hired Geoff Melkonian (bass/viola/vocals) and Jason Buecker (drums/percussion/vocals) to accompany him to play shows together. They simply called themselves Josh Joplin Band.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Walton|first=A. Scott|url=|title=Peach Buzz|date=April 6, 1995|work=Atlanta Journal Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>  In late 1995 they began pre-production on their first album together. Recorded at Furies Studios with producer Ed Burdell ([[Magnapop]]),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/ed-burdell-mn0000144299|title=All Music|last=Burdell|first=Ed|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Projector Head<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=DeVault|first=Russ|url=|title=Weekend Preview, Guide To Music Midtown|date=May 3, 1996|work=The Atlanta Journal Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> was released, January 6, 1996.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Hamilton|first=Doug|url=|title=Weekend Preview, Concert Preview|date=January 5, 1996|work=The Atlanta Journal Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>  Based on local critical success and some airplay on local radio <ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Various-Peach-Jam-1997/release/8495065|title=Various - Peach Jam 1997|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Joplin, Buecker, and Melkonian, began touring vigorously. Starting in the south, continuing through the northeast, and beyond.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gambill|first=Rex|url=|title=Projector Head: Josh Joplin Band|date=December 27, 1996|work=The Coschocton Tribune, Coshocton Ohio|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''Boxing Nostalgic''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Josh-Joplin-Band-Boxing-Nostalgic/release/11443808|title=Josh Joplin Band - Boxing Nostalgic|last=Joplin|first=Josh|date=|website=Discogs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1430711/shawn-mullins-inks-deal-with-josh-joplin-band/|title=Shawn Mullins Inks Deal With Josh Joplin Band|last=News Staff|first=Mtv|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Music Around Town|date=August 1, 1997|work=The Atlanta Journal Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> was their self produced sophomore effort. It was released April 6th, 1997 to a sold out show at the Cotton Club<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hamilton|first=Doug|url=|title=Joplin Learning Reality Of Recording Business|date=April 4, 1997|work=The Atlanta Journal Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>  The album introduced piano to their sound and Allen Broyles who played on the record would join the band that same year.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hamilton|first=Doug|url=|title=In Concert This Weekend|date=May 21, 1999|work=The Atlanta-Journal Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>  The band continued touring and opening shows for [[Jump, Little Children]], [[Five Eight (band)|Five Eight]], [[The Innocence Mission]], [[Ben Harper]], Nathan Sheppard, Kitty Snyder, among others.\n\nIn 1998, having played the [[Roxy Theatre (Atlanta)]] opening for [[Shawn Mullins]] the [[Grammy Award|Grammy]]-nominated songwriter of [[Lullaby (Shawn Mullins song)|Lullaby]], the band discussed making their third album with their friend and Mullins signed on as the producer hiring  [[Anthony J. Resta discography|Anthony J. Resta]] to create the beats and programming for it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/useful-music-mw0000112721/credits|title=Useful Music Credits|last=Resta|first=Anthony J.|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  He would later release the album entitled, [[Useful Music]], on his own SMG label.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nowtoronto.com/music/album-reviews/josh-joplin-group/|title=New and Notable Releases|last=Hughes|first=Kim|date=February 2001|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>   Shortly after its release, Jason Buecker was replaced on drums by [[Ani Cordero]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wamc.org/post/rogovoy-report-10617|title=WAMC Midday Magazine|last=Rogovoy|first=Seth|date=October 17, 2017|website=WAMC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> then Eric Taylor who drummed for legendary dream pop founders, [[Seely (band)|Seely]] (on [[Too Pure]] Records).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/91118-Seely|title=Seely|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  Deeds Davis was added to play lead guitar and sing.\n\nThe band was managed briefly by [[Nettwerk]] Music Group<ref>{{Cite news|last=Eldredge|first=Richard L.|url=|title=Peach Buzz|date=August 16, 1999|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> before making a slight name change to Josh Joplin Group when [[Artemis Records]] headed by legendary industry moguls [[Danny Goldberg]] <ref>{{Cite news|last=Boyce|first=Kevin|url=|title=King Midas|date=January 23, 2003|work=CMJ|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Daniel Glass]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://creativeloafing.com/content-159675-paper-tiger|title=Paper Tiger|last=Sarig|first=Roni|date=August 1, 2001|website=Creative Loafing|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> signed them to their label.  They were picked up by [[Indigo Girls]] <ref>{{Cite news|last=Black|first=Alan|url=https://smartech.gatech.edu/bitstream/handle/1853/7873/music_midtown-2001-06-01.pdf?sequence=3&isAllowed=y|title=Music Midtown 2001|date=June 1, 2001|work=Recaps|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Matthew Sweet]] manager, Russell Carter.\n\nThe Artemis re-release would feature an alternative version of Joplin's ballad, I've Changed. It was lavishly produced by [[Peter Collins (record producer)|Peter Collins]] at Nashville's [[Ocean Way Recording]] studio, with [[Kenny Aronoff]] playing drums.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/kenny-aronoff-mn0000081149/credits|title=Kenny Aronoff Discography|last=Aronoff|first=Kenny|date=|website=All Music|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  A slightly more successful collaboration came when ex-[[The Modern Lovers|Modern Lover]] / [[Talking Heads|Talking Head,]] [[Jerry Harrison]] was brought on produce the opening track, Matter and Joplin's new song, Camera One, which hadn't been previously released.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailyvault.com/toc.php5?review=1827|title=Daily Vault|last=Warburg|first=Jason|date=February 15, 2002|website=Daily Vault|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Jenkins|first=Daniel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OxEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA20&lpg=PA20&dq=jerry+harrison+and+Josh+Joplin+group&source=bl&ots=pV-WQ4xtHb&sig=ACfU3U2MzvZzTDuj4LH4VxMi-1n0E1WnFw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj15PDHw97oAhUJLs0KHW4UCwYQ6AEwB3oECA4QKQ#v=onepage&q=jerry%20harrison%20and%20Josh%20Joplin%20group&f=false|title=Billboard|date=December 16, 2000|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Josh-Joplin-Group-Camera-One-2/release/3038187|title=Useful Music Camera One +2|last=Group|first=Josh Joplin|date=2000|website=Discogs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe album came out in January 30, 2001<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sperounes|first=Sandra|url=https://edmontonjournal.com|title=Ten On Tuesday|date=January 27, 2001|work=Edmonton Journal|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Lindquist|first=David|url=https://www.indystar.com|title=Joplin Spins Musical Tales|date=October 11, 2001|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> to strong reviews<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jenkins|first=Daniel|url=|title=Josh Joplin Group Serves Up Useful Music|date=December 16, 2001|work=Billboard|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nowtoronto.com/music/album-reviews/josh-joplin-group/|title=Now|last=Hughes|first=Kim|date=February 1, 2001|website=Now Toronto|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and sold over 100,000 records in its first week.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Schwartz|first=Daylle Deanna|title=Start And Run Your Own Record Label|publisher=Billboard Books|year=2003|isbn=0-8230-8433-7|location=NY, NY|pages=151}}</ref> It's single, \"Camera One,\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.popradiotop20.com/Year/RR-HAC-2001-Year.htm|title=Hot AC Chart 2001|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> was the first independent release to go [[List of Billboard number-one adult alternative singles of the 2000s#2000|number-one]] at Triple A radio <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Billboard_number-one_adult_alternative_singles_of_the_2000s|title=List Of Billboard #1adult alternative singles|last=Company|first=Neilson|date=March 3, 2001|website=Billboard|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and went to number 22 on the ''[[Billboard magazine|Billboard]]'' Top 40 chart in 2001. It won the \"Single Of The Year\" award by the [[American Association of Independent Music]]. Useful Music songs were featured in many of the top rated shows of the time, including [[Party of Five]], [[Dawson's Creek]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tunefind.com/show/dawsons-creek/season-4/19274|title=Dawson's Creek Episode: Promicide|last=|first=|date=May 2, 2001|website=Tunefind|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [[Northern Exposure]], and Camera One was a feature of an episode of the comedy series ''[[Scrubs (TV series)|Scrubs]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tunefind.com/show/scrubs/season-1/716|title=Scrubs Season 1|last=|first=|date=November 6, 2001|website=TuneFind|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nJosh Joplin Group toured America, Mexico, Canada, Australia, and all of Europe. They played shows with countless bands, and artists including [[Travis (band)|Travis,]] [[Old 97's]], [[Matthew Sweet]],  [[Uncle Green]], [[Yeah Yeah Yeahs]], [[Lifehouse (band)|Lifehouse,]] [[Pink (singer)|Pink,]] [[Smoke (American band)|Smoke,]] <ref>{{Cite news|last=Harrison|first=Shane|url=|title=99x Main Stage Preview Have Your Cake|date=September 17, 1999|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Gincel|first=Richard|url=|title=College Night at The High Museum|date=April 6, 1995|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> and had finished performing a German festival in Cologne, when [[Green Day]] burned their drums on stage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cs.cmu.edu/~ckaestne/concerts.xhtml|title=Every Concert Ever|last=|first=|date=August 17, 2001|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.concertarchives.org/bands/blumfeld|title=Concert Archives: Bizarre Festival Line Up 2001|last=|first=|date=August 17, 2001|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The band has also appeared on [[Late Night with Conan O'Brien]], [[Late Show with David Letterman]], [[The Late Late Show with Craig Ferguson]], [[The Panel (Australian TV series)]], [[The Mike Bullard Show]], [[Viva (TV station)|Viva TV (Germany)]], [[MTV]], [[VH1]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Owens|first=Clay|url=https://www.stardem.com|title=The Pursuit Of Happiness|date=January 11, 2008|work=The Star-Democrat|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn June of 2002, Josh Joplin began working on demos for songwriter turned producer, [[Fountains of Wayne]]'s [[Adam Schlesinger]]. Schlesinger was tapped to produce the groups sophomore Artemis release. He recorded 12 songs acoustically at [[Stratosphere Sound]], (owned by Schlesinger and [[James Iha]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/513906/a-studio-a-smashing-pumpkin-can-call-home/|title=A Studio A Smashing Pumpkin Can Call Home|last=Hiatt|first=Brian|date=April 30, 1999|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  And although the timing didn't work out for the two to work together, Josh and the group, sans Davis, did end up recording   ''[[The Future That Was]].''<ref>{{Cite news|last=Scarrone|first=John|url=|title=Future That Was' One Of 2002's Best|date=January 7, 2003|work=Poughkeepsie Journal|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> with Atlanta producer, Rob Gal and engineers, John Holbrook and Rudyard Lee Cullers <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/rob-gal-mn0000828329/credits|title=The Future That Was|last=Gal|first=Rob|date=August 1, 2002|website=All Music|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/john-holbrook-mn0000226375|title=The Future That Was|last=Holbrook|first=John|date=August 1, 2002|website=All Music|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/rudyard-lee-cullers-mn0000527241|title=The Future That Was|last=Cullers|first=Rudyard Lee|date=June 1, 2002|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> at Stratosphere.  On this record, the musical styles were similarly varied, ranging from slow piano- and acoustic guitar-driven pop to upbeat keyboard- and electric guitar-based rock.\n\n''The Future That Was'' received critical acclaim<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?id=5165&name=Josh+Joplin+Group|title=Robert Christgau Dean Of American Rock Critics|last=Christgau|first=Robert|date=September 9, 2003|website=Robert Christgau|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Goings On About Town|date=November 18, 2002|work=The New Yorker|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/music/josh-joplin/josh-joplin-group-the-future-that-was/|title=The Future That Was Review|last=Moye|first=Jay|date=April 1, 2003|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Knodel|first=Lisa|url=|title=The Future That Was (Rocked!)|date=October 4, 2002|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Eldridge|first=Richard|url=|title=Joplin Letting A Little Optimism Be Heard|date=September 23, 2002|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Fuller|first=Cam|url=|title=Joplin's Insight Raises The Flesh|date=April 10, 2002|work=Star Phoenix|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Leslie|first=Karl|url=|title=Josh Joplin Group Future That Was Review|date=November 28, 2002|work=St. Cloud Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thepitchkc.com/josh-joplin/|title=Josh Joplin|last=Kreicbergs|first=John|date=October 31, 2002|website=The Pitch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> but it sold poorly and Artemis released dropped the band from their contract.  Artemis released two singles from the album, \"I Am Not the Only Cowboy\" and \"Wonder Wheel,\" but neither one took off. In the fall of 2003, the band announced that it was breaking up and would play its final two shows in [[Atlanta]] in December of that year.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Josh Joplin Band===\n\n*''Projector Head''\n** Release Date: January 6, 1996\n** Label: Self-released\n*''Boxing Nostalgic''\n** Release Date: April 6, 1997\n** Label: Self-released\n*''[[Useful Music]]''\n** Release Date: May 25, 1999\n** Label: SMG Records\n\n===Josh Joplin Group===\n*''[[Useful Music]]''\n** Release Date: January 23, 2001\n** Label: [[Artemis Records]], [[Sony Music]] (Europe), [[Epic Records]] (Australia, South Africa)\n*''[[The Future That Was]]''\n** Release Date: September 24, 2002\n** Label: Artemis Records\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n<!--==External links==-->\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:American pop music groups]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Josh Joplin Group\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| background       = Group_or_Band\n| years_active     = 1995\u20132002\n| origin           = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], United States\n| genre            = [[Alternative rock]]<br />[[Folk Rock]]<br />[[Americana music{{!}}]]<br />[[Rock music|Rock]]<br />\n| label            = [[Independent music|Independent]], SMG, [[Artemis Records|Artemis]] [[Sony]], [[Epic]]{{dn|date=April 2020}}\n| associated_acts  = \n| current_members  = \n| past_members     = [[Josh Joplin]]<br />Geoff Melkonian<br />Jason Buecker<br />Allen Broyles<br />Deeds Davis<br />[[Ani Cordero]]<br />Eric Taylor\n| website          = \n}}\n'''Josh Joplin Group''' was an Atlanta, [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]-based [[Rock music|rock]] band led by [[singer-songwriter]] [[Josh Joplin]]. Initially a trio, Joplin hired Geoff Melkonian (bass/viola/vocals) and Jason Buecker (drums/percussion/vocals) to accompany him to play shows together. They simply called themselves Josh Joplin Band<ref>{{Cite news|last=Walton|first=A. Scott|url=|title=Peach Buzz|date=April 6, 1995|work=Atlanta Journal Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>.  In late 1995 they began pre-production on their first album together. Recorded at Furies Studios with producer Ed Burdell ([[Magnapop]]),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/ed-burdell-mn0000144299|title=All Music|last=Burdell|first=Ed|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Projector Head<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=DeVault|first=Russ|url=|title=Weekend Preview, Guide To Music Midtown|date=May 3, 1996|work=The Atlanta Journal Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> was released, January 6, 1996<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Hamilton|first=Doug|url=|title=Weekend Preview, Concert Preview|date=January 5, 1996|work=The Atlanta Journal Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>.  Based on local critical success and some airplay on local radio <ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Various-Peach-Jam-1997/release/8495065|title=Various - Peach Jam 1997|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Joplin, Buecker, and Melkonian, began touring vigorously. Starting in the south, continuing through the northeast, and beyond<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gambill|first=Rex|url=|title=Projector Head: Josh Joplin Band|date=December 27, 1996|work=The Coschocton Tribune, Coshocton Ohio|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>.  \n\n''Boxing Nostalgic''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Josh-Joplin-Band-Boxing-Nostalgic/release/11443808|title=Josh Joplin Band - Boxing Nostalgic|last=Joplin|first=Josh|date=|website=Discogs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> <ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1430711/shawn-mullins-inks-deal-with-josh-joplin-band/|title=Shawn Mullins Inks Deal With Josh Joplin Band|last=News Staff|first=Mtv|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Music Around Town|date=August 1, 1997|work=The Atlanta Journal Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>was their self produced sophomore effort. It was released April 6th, 1997 to a sold out show at the Cotton Club<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hamilton|first=Doug|url=|title=Joplin Learning Reality Of Recording Business|date=April 4, 1997|work=The Atlanta Journal Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>  The album introduced piano to their sound and Allen Broyles who played on the record would join the band that same year.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hamilton|first=Doug|url=|title=In Concert This Weekend|date=May 21, 1999|work=The Atlanta-Journal Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>  The band continued touring and opening shows for [[Jump, Little Children]], [[Five Eight (band)|Five Eight]], [[The Innocence Mission]], [[Ben Harper]], Nathan Sheppard, Kitty Snyder, among others. \n\nIn 1998, having played the [[Roxy Theatre (Atlanta)]] opening for [[Shawn Mullins]] the [[Grammy Award|Grammy]]-nominated songwriter of [[Lullaby (Shawn Mullins song)|Lullaby]], the band discussed making their third album with their friend and Mullins signed on as the producer hiring  [[Anthony J. Resta discography|Anthony J. Resta]] to create the beats and programming for it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/useful-music-mw0000112721/credits|title=Useful Music Credits|last=Resta|first=Anthony J.|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  He would later release the album entitled, [[Useful Music]], on his own SMG label.<ref name=\":2\" /> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nowtoronto.com/music/album-reviews/josh-joplin-group/|title=New and Notable Releases|last=Hughes|first=Kim|date=February 2001|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>   Shortly after its release, Jason Buecker was replaced on drums by [[Ani Cordero]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wamc.org/post/rogovoy-report-10617|title=WAMC Midday Magazine|last=Rogovoy|first=Seth|date=October 17, 2017|website=WAMC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> then Eric Taylor who drummed for legendary dream pop founders, [[Seely (band)|Seely]] (on [[Too Pure]] Records)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/91118-Seely|title=Seely|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.  Deeds Davis was added to play lead guitar and sing. \n\nThe band was managed briefly by [[Nettwerk]] Music Group<ref>{{Cite news|last=Eldredge|first=Richard L.|url=|title=Peach Buzz|date=August 16, 1999|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> before making a slight name change to Josh Joplin Group when [[Artemis Records]] headed by legendary industry moguls [[Danny Goldberg]] <ref>{{Cite news|last=Boyce|first=Kevin|url=|title=King Midas|date=January 23,  2003|work=CMJ|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Daniel Glass]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://creativeloafing.com/content-159675-paper-tiger|title=Paper Tiger|last=Sarig|first=Roni|date=August 1, 2001|website=Creative Loafing|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. signed them to their label.  They were picked up by [[Indigo Girls]] <ref>{{Cite news|last=Black|first=Alan|url=https://smartech.gatech.edu/bitstream/handle/1853/7873/music_midtown-2001-06-01.pdf?sequence=3&isAllowed=y|title=Music Midtown 2001|date=June 1, 2001|work=Recaps|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>and [[Matthew Sweet]] manager, Russell Carter. \n\nThe Artemis re-release would feature an alternative version of Joplin's ballad, I've Changed. It was lavishly produced by [[Peter Collins (record producer)|Peter Collins]] at Nashville's [[Ocean Way Recording]] studio, with [[Kenny Aronoff]] playing drums. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/kenny-aronoff-mn0000081149/credits|title=Kenny Aronoff Discography|last=Aronoff|first=Kenny|date=|website=All Music|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  A slightly more successful collaboration came when ex-[[The Modern Lovers|Modern Lover]] / [[Talking Heads|Talking Head,]] [[Jerry Harrison]] was brought on produce the opening track, Matter and Joplin's new song, Camera One, which hadn't been previously released.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailyvault.com/toc.php5?review=1827|title=Daily Vault|last=Warburg|first=Jason|date=February 15, 2002|website=Daily Vault|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Jenkins|first=Daniel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OxEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA20&lpg=PA20&dq=jerry+harrison+and+Josh+Joplin+group&source=bl&ots=pV-WQ4xtHb&sig=ACfU3U2MzvZzTDuj4LH4VxMi-1n0E1WnFw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj15PDHw97oAhUJLs0KHW4UCwYQ6AEwB3oECA4QKQ#v=onepage&q=jerry%20harrison%20and%20Josh%20Joplin%20group&f=false|title=Billboard|date=December 16, 2000|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Josh-Joplin-Group-Camera-One-2/release/3038187|title=Useful Music Camera One +2|last=Group|first=Josh Joplin|date=2000|website=Discogs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nThe album came out in January 30, 2001<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sperounes|first=Sandra|url=https://edmontonjournal.com|title=Ten On Tuesday|date=January 27, 2001|work=Edmonton Journal|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|last=Lindquist|first=David|url=https://www.indystar.com|title=Joplin Spins Musical Tales|date=October 11, 2001|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>to strong reviews<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jenkins|first=Daniel|url=|title=Josh Joplin Group Serves Up Useful Music|date=December 16, 2001|work=Billboard|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nowtoronto.com/music/album-reviews/josh-joplin-group/|title=Now|last=Hughes|first=Kim|date=February 1, 2001|website=Now Toronto|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and sold over 100,000 records in its first week.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Schwartz|first=Daylle Deanna|title=Start And Run Your Own Record Label|publisher=Billboard Books|year=2003|isbn=0-8230-8433-7|location=NY, NY|pages=151}}</ref> It's single, \"Camera One,\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.popradiotop20.com/Year/RR-HAC-2001-Year.htm|title=Hot AC Chart 2001|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> was the first independent release to go [[List of Billboard number-one adult alternative singles of the 2000s#2000|number-one]] at Triple A radio <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Billboard_number-one_adult_alternative_singles_of_the_2000s|title=List Of Billboard #1adult alternative singles|last=Company|first=Neilson|date=March 3, 2001|website=Billboard|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>and went to number 22 on the ''[[Billboard magazine|Billboard]]'' Top 40 chart in 2001. It won the \"Single Of The Year\" award by the [[American Association of Independent Music]]. Useful Music songs were featured in many of the top rated shows of the time, including [[Party of Five]], [[Dawson's Creek]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tunefind.com/show/dawsons-creek/season-4/19274|title=Dawson's Creek Episode: Promicide|last=|first=|date=May 2, 2001|website=Tunefind|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, [[Northern Exposure]], and Camera One was a feature of an episode of the comedy series ''[[Scrubs (TV series)|Scrubs]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tunefind.com/show/scrubs/season-1/716|title=Scrubs Season 1|last=|first=|date=November 6, 2001|website=TuneFind|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nJosh Joplin Group toured America, Mexico, Canada, Australia, and all of Europe. They played shows with countless bands, and artists including [[Travis (band)|Travis,]] [[Old 97's]], [[Matthew Sweet]],  [[Uncle Green]], [[Yeah Yeah Yeahs]], [[Lifehouse (band)|Lifehouse,]] [[Pink (singer)|Pink,]] [[Smoke (American band)|Smoke,]] <ref>{{Cite news|last=Harrison|first=Shane|url=|title=99x Main Stage Preview Have Your Cake|date=September 17, 1999|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Gincel|first=Richard|url=|title=College Night at The High Museum|date=April 6, 1995|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>and had finished performing a German festival in Cologne, when [[Green Day]] burned their drums on stage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cs.cmu.edu/~ckaestne/concerts.xhtml|title=Every Concert Ever|last=|first=|date=August 17, 2001|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.concertarchives.org/bands/blumfeld|title=Concert Archives: Bizarre Festival Line Up 2001|last=|first=|date=August 17, 2001|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>The band has also appeared on [[Late Night with Conan O'Brien]], [[Late Show with David Letterman]], [[The Late Late Show with Craig Ferguson]], [[The Panel (Australian TV series)]], [[The Mike Bullard Show]], [[Viva (TV station)|Viva TV (Germany)]], [[MTV]], [[VH1]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Owens|first=Clay|url=https://www.stardem.com|title=The Pursuit Of Happiness|date=January 11, 2008|work=The Star-Democrat|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn June of 2002, Josh Joplin began working on demos for songwriter turned producer, [[Fountains of Wayne]]'s [[Adam Schlesinger]]. Schlesinger was tapped to produce the groups sophomore Artemis release. He recorded 12 songs acoustically at [[Stratosphere Sound]], (owned by Schlesinger and [[James Iha]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/513906/a-studio-a-smashing-pumpkin-can-call-home/|title=A Studio A Smashing Pumpkin Can Call Home|last=Hiatt|first=Brian|date=April 30, 1999|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  And although the timing didn't work out for the two to work together, Josh and the group, sans Davis, did end up recording   ''[[The Future That Was]].''<ref>{{Cite news|last=Scarrone|first=John|url=|title=Future That Was' One Of 2002's Best|date=January 7, 2003|work=Poughkeepsie Journal|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> with Atlanta producer, Rob Gal and engineers, John Holbrook and Rudyard Lee Cullers <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/rob-gal-mn0000828329/credits|title=The Future That Was|last=Gal|first=Rob|date=August 1, 2002|website=All Music|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/john-holbrook-mn0000226375|title=The Future That Was|last=Holbrook|first=John|date=August 1, 2002|website=All Music|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/rudyard-lee-cullers-mn0000527241|title=The Future That Was|last=Cullers|first=Rudyard Lee|date=June 1, 2002|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> at Stratosphere.  On this record, the musical styles were similarly varied, ranging from slow piano- and acoustic guitar-driven pop to upbeat keyboard- and electric guitar-based rock.\n\n''The Future That Was'' received critical acclaim<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?id=5165&name=Josh+Joplin+Group|title=Robert Christgau Dean Of American Rock Critics|last=Christgau|first=Robert|date=September 9, 2003|website=Robert Christgau|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Goings On About Town|date=November 18, 2002|work=The New Yorker|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/music/josh-joplin/josh-joplin-group-the-future-that-was/|title=The Future That Was Review|last=Moye|first=Jay|date=April 1, 2003|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Knodel|first=Lisa|url=|title=The Future That Was (Rocked!)|date=October 4, 2002|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Eldridge|first=Richard|url=|title=Joplin Letting A Little Optimism Be Heard|date=September 23, 2002|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|last=Fuller|first=Cam|url=|title=Joplin's Insight Raises The Flesh|date=April 10, 2002|work=Star Phoenix|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Leslie|first=Karl|url=|title=Josh Joplin Group Future That Was Review|date=November 28, 2002|work=St. Cloud Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thepitchkc.com/josh-joplin/|title=Josh Joplin|last=Kreicbergs|first=John|date=October 31, 2002|website=The Pitch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>but it sold poorly and Artemis released dropped the band from their contract.  Artemis released two singles from the album, \"I Am Not the Only Cowboy\" and \"Wonder Wheel,\" but neither one took off. In the fall of 2003, the band announced that it was breaking up and would play its final two shows in [[Atlanta]] in December of that year.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Josh Joplin Band===\n\n*''Projector Head''\n** Release Date: January 6,1996\n** Label: Self-released\n*''Boxing Nostalgic''\n** Release Date: April 6, 1997\n** Label: Self-released\n*''[[Useful Music]]''\n** Release Date: May 25, 1999\n** Label: SMG Records\n\n===Josh Joplin Group===\n*''[[Useful Music]]''\n** Release Date: January 23, 2001\n** Label: [[Artemis Records]], [[Sony Music]] (Europe), [[Epic Records]] (Australia, South Africa)\n*''[[The Future That Was]]''\n** Release Date: September 24, 2002\n** Label: Artemis Records\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:American pop music groups]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josh_Joplin_Group"}
